<HEADLINE> Germany Favors Multilateralism: Fischer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Germany said Wednesday
it is committed to multilaterism and the strengthening of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"In the international state system of tomorrow the answer to
the challenges of globalization will come from multilateralism
alone," said Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer.
</P>
<P>
He told the 54th Session of the U.N. General Assembly that the
world "will always be plural and no form of unilateralism can work
in the long run".
</P>
<P>
The 21st century will need a United Nations capable of taking
action, he said at the general debate, adding that Germany will be
"the staunchest" ally of the U.N. member states in the efforts to
strengthen the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Among the issues he touched upon is the development cooperation
between the developed and developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Within the framework of its European Union and Group of Eight
countries Presidencies, Germany launched substantial initiatives
which must be further developed in the form of the 1999 Cologne
Debt Initiative, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the G-8 summit in Cologne in June Germany called for
creditor countries to speed up the debt relief process for the
heavily indebted countries by ascertaining the extent and date of
the debt relief by 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
