<HEADLINE> Holiday Online Sales in U.S. Expected to Double This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Online sales in the
United States are expected to double this holiday season,
according to a new research report released this week by leading
Internet research firm Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
E-commerce sales in November and December could reach 6 billion
U.S. dollars, up from an estimated 3.1 billion dollars spent
during the same period in 1998. Jupiter expects online shopping to
grow to 78 billion dollars by 2003.
</P>
<P>
Jupiter also expects that 10 million online users in the United
States will begin shopping in 1999 and many will make their first
purchases during the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
But Jupiter researchers warned that e-tailers will have to deal
with issues, such as site failures, inadequate customer service
and poor order fulfillment, if they want to stay in the game.
</P>
<P>
One area that sites should address is performance. Jupiter
expects traffic volume to grow enormously at leading retail sites
this holiday season, jumping from an average 15,000 transactions
per day between January and October to 58,000 transactions per day
during the winter holidays.
</P>
<P>
Another U.S. research firm, Forrester Researcher, predicted
this week that online retail sales in North America will be worth
184 billion U.S. dollars by 2004. Further, the Internet will
influence another 500 billion dollars worth of goods purchased
offline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
