<HEADLINE> Duma Approves Amendment on Parliamentary Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The State Duma on Wednesday
approved, during its first reading, a constitutional amendment
that would strengthen parliament's role in investigations.
</P>
<P>
The amendment was backed, in a second vote, by 300 deputies,
the required minimum of votes needed for the bill to clear the
lower house of parliament, the Interfax news agency reported. A
first try was four votes short of the required minimum.
</P>
<P>
Under the approved amendment, the State Duma shall have the
right to set up commissions for handling matters of public
interest.
</P>
<P>
The attendance of individuals called to commission sessions and
the presentation of all the required documents is mandatory.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers believe that parliamentary investigations will
become a key form of the State Duma's control over the state's
government agencies, including the Cabinet and its individual
members, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
However, President Boris Yeltsin's representative in the Duma,
Alexander Kotenkov, opposed the bill, saying that that by
introducing the concept of parliamentary commissions, the State
Duma is trying to secure the word "parliament" for only one
chamber. He also said that by setting up such a commission, the
Duma is going beyond the limits of its powers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
