<HEADLINE> S. African Parliament Approves Heritage Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The South African
National Assembly on Wednesday unanimously approved the World
Heritage Convention Bill, paving the way for three of South
Africa's most important cultural and natural sites, including
Robben Island, to be granted world heritage site status.
</P>
<P>
The declaration, by the United Nations Environmental, Social
and Cultural Organization (UNESCO), is expected to take place in
December this year, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The bill will create the legal and administrative framework
necessary for heritage status.
</P>
<P>
Introducing the debate, Deputy Environment Minister Joyce
Mabudafhasi said the government was confident that UNESCO would
give South Africa's first three nominations -- Robben Island, the
hominid site at Sterkfontein, and the greater St Lucia wetlands --
their rightful status in the world alongside the Acropolis in
Athens, the Grand Canyon in America, and Great Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
South Africa intended to add others, such as the Drakensberg,
to the list, she said.
</P>
<P>
Speakers from various parties agreed that the status of the
three areas as world heritage sites would enhance South Africa's
tourist industry at a time when it was vital to economic growth
and job creation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
