<HEADLINE> Pakistan Suits India over Aircraft Shooting-Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Wednesday
brought a case against India to the International Court of Justice
(ICJ) over the shooting down of a Pakistani aircraft by Indian air
force planes on August 10.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan contends that the unarmed aircraft was on a routine
training mission in the country's own airspace with 16 personnel
on board who were all killed when it was hit without warning by
Indian air force planes, a U.N. spokesman told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is charging that this action violated the U.N. Charter
and an agreement between India and Pakistan on the Prevention of
Air Space Violations, spokesman Manoel de Almeida e Silva said.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan also says the incident violated obligations under
customary international law not to use force and not to violate
another state's sovereignty," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to information from the Hague-based ICJ, Pakistan
requested that ICJ order India to make reparations to Pakistan for
the loss of the aircraft and the lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
