<HEADLINE> IDB Supports Modernization of Firms in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) announced Wednesday the approval of a loan
of 140 million U.S. dollars to Argentina to support the
modernization of firms through the use of technology.
</P>
<P>
The resources will assist enterprises producing goods and
services, mainly those that are small and medium-sized, in order
that they may initiate, import, alter or adapt technologies to
increase their efficiency and competitiveness, the
Washington-based IDB said.
</P>
<P>
The program provides mechanisms and incentives for
technological innovation through credit and noncredit co-financing
instruments that include up to 50 percent of the cost of projects
submitted by enterprises for development and improvements of
products and processes.
</P>
<P>
The resources will also finance the development of strategic
and scientific research capacities to meet priorities of the
productive sectors, especially those in geographic areas with
special needs.
</P>
<P>
The project will apply international technological advances and
operations of previous technology programs in Argentina,
especially those that benefit small and medium-sized enterprises,
so as to produce products with a higher value added and to
contribute to a more dynamic economy.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the program, which will be carried out by the
Secretariat of Science and Technology of the Ministry of Culture
and Education, is 280 million dollars. The IDB loan is for a
20-year term, with a four year grace period, at the variable
annual interest rate, now 6.84 percent. Local counterpart funds
total 140 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
