<HEADLINE> Ibero-American Economy to Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Ibero-American economy will
rebound in the last quarter of the year, according to a study
performed by the Spanish financial unit "Argentaria", made public
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
For the Department of Studies of Argentaria, this tendency will
continue in the year 2000, until the Gross Domestic Product (GDP)
of the region reaches 3.4 per cent.
</P>
<P>
In spite of a forecast fall of 0.6 per cent of the GDP for this
year, the Ibero-American economy will register growth over the
last quarter.
</P>
<P>
The study done by Argentaria also shows a slight fall in the
rate of unemployment, which should reduce from the present level
of nine per cent to 8 per cent in the year 2000. Inflation is also
forecast to reduce slightly from the 8 per cent of this year to
7.5 per cent next year, due to the deceleration of the price rises
in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
As a consequence of the evolution of the level of activity, a
forecast is made for improvement in the deficit of the public
sector, especially notable in Brazil and Colombia, and only a
slight rise in the deficit of the current account.
</P>
<P>
Ibero-America is composed by all Latin American countries plus
Spain and Portugal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
