<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Committed to Decentralization: Acting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Acting President
Simon Muzenda said Wednesday that his government is committed to
the process of devolving responsibilities and functions to local
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The decision to devolve responsibilities was made on the
philosophy that important developmental views arise from the
people at grassroots level, Muzenda said when officially opening
an African ministers conference on local government systems in the
resort town of Victoria Falls.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, the people have to be given appropriate structures
through which they can be involved in programs and projects that
benefit them," he said.
</P>
<P>
"To this effect, our parliament has passed laws to provide for
democratic participatory structures at village, ward, district and
provincial levels," he added.
</P>
<P>
The acting president said appropriate institutional structures
to implement and monitor the transfer of powers and functions to
the local authorities have also been put in place.
</P>
<P>
"We have been mindful of the fact that our decentralization
program is taking place at a time when we are also implementing
economic structural reforms," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that local governments in Africa are going to
deal with issues of attracting capital and investment, creating
jobs, combating poverty and crime and protecting the environment.
</P>
<P>
"The importance of building strong local governments in Africa,
 therefore, cannot be over-emphasized," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is through strengthened local governments that there is a
higher likelihood of reflecting local needs more accurately than
centralized systems of government," Muzenda said.
</P>
<P>
He said decentralized and democratic local governance has
become the vehicle through which people are going to have a voice
and choice in matters affecting their daily lives.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said the African ministers conference came at an
appropriate time to enable participants to prepare for the next
summit of African cities to be held in Namibia early next year.
</P>
<P>
The conference would enable the 14 countries represented to
learn from each other's experience in adopting decentralization
strategies and actions.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Worried About Rapid Population Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Minister of
State Edward Lowassa Wednesday expressed worries that the fast
growth of population could hamper the east African country's
development.
</P>
<P>
While launching the State of World Population 1999 Report in
Dar es Salaam, Lowassa said Tanzania's population is estimated to
have reached 31. 8 million by the middle of this year compared
with 23.1 million in1988 and 7.7 million in 1948.
</P>
<P>
But the country's annual population growth rate has declined to
2.8 percent from 3.2 percent during the period from 1978 to 1988,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Though there is a decline in growth rate, the number of people
added to the population each year amounts to 880,000 a year
currently, compared with 660,000 a decade ago, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"We do understand that population growth ... is not necessarily
an obstacle to development," he said. "But rapid population
growth, out of proportion with the nation's wealth creation
momentum, can be a serious impediments to improvement of the
quality of life," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's economic growth rate stands at between 3.5 percent
and 4.0 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
Lowassa said the rapid population growth tends to increase
outlays on consumption, drawing resources away from savings for
productive investment and, therefore, tends to retard growth in
national output through slow capital formation.
</P>
<P>
The strains caused by rapid population growth are felt most
acutely and visibly in the public budgets for health, education
and other sectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
S.B. Buberwa, director of Social Services at the Planning
Commission, told Xinhua that the Tanzanian government has set up
maternal health clinics across the country, providing free
contraceptives for people to adopt family planning.
</P>
<P>
However, contraceptives are not available to all people for
lack of resources from donors, he said.
</P>
<P>
Demographic experts said that many people are reluctant to use
the devices due to religious or cultural reasons.
</P>
<P>
However, contraceptive prevalence rate in Tanzania rose from
6.3 percent in 1992 to 16 percent in 1996. But the rate is still
below a goal set at the International Conference on Population and
Development in Cairo in 1994, Lowassa said.
</P>
<P>
The minister did not say what measures would be taken to slow
down the population growth rate, but he stressed the importance of
reproductive health care services.
</P>
<P>
With respect to quality and accessibility of reproductive
health services, about 48 percent of all deliveries are attended
by health professionals and 47 percent of deliveries take place in
health facilities.
</P>
<P>
In addition there is high unmet need of reproductive health
services, he added.
</P>
<P>
Teferi Seyoum, representative of the United Nations Population
Fund (UNFPA) in Tanzania, said that 22 women in the country die
daily from preventable pregnancy-relation complications.
</P>
<P>
Buberwa said that the government adopted a national population
policy in 1992, which has enhanced people's awareness of family
planning.
</P>
<P>
He added that the government will continue to review policies
to link reproductive health with family planning, and to address
environment, gender and other issues.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Buberwa said Tanzania will mobilize resources
to provide more family planning services to people, and carry out
education among women to arouse their awareness of the importance
of a smaller family size.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
