<HEADLINE> Russian Rocket Sends Four U.S. Satellites Into Orbit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A Russian Soyuz-U booster
rocket with four Globalstar communication satellites lifted off
from the Baikonur cosmodrome in Wednesday, the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
This was the first of three launches of Globalstar satellites
on board Russian Soyuz rockets scheduled for this autumn. The next
two are expected in October and November, Interfax said, quoting
the Russian Strategic Rocket Forces press service.
</P>
<P>
Three earlier launches were made in February, March and April.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Globalstar company chose to use Russian rockets to
launch its satellites after the Ukrainian Zenit rocket crashed in
September 1998 and Globalstar lost 12 space probes, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Globalstar's new generation personal mobile communication
network will consist of 52 low-orbit satellites and a global
network of ground stations. Nineteen stations are under
construction in different parts of the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
