<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Redirect Health Research to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Research on health done in
Africa has benefited the international community more than the
African continent itself, Zimbabwean Health and Child Welfare
Minister Timothy Stamps said in Harare Monday.
</P>
<P>
At the opening of a four-day conference on African health
research for development, the minister said the African continent
has become the research laboratory for the world in which there
are few ethical consideration for the researched.
</P>
<P>
"African research is dedicated to interests outside Africa and
this must be redirected to benefit local communities," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Stamps asked the participants at the conference to resolve how
policy and decision makers could exploit the intellectual social
capital on the African continent to benefit local communities.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 participants from various African countries were
attending this conference which would examine the linkages between
health research program and policy formulation.
</P>
<P>
This would be done to enhance the impact of research on health
development in Africa, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Stamps also asked the participants to come up with Africa-based
journals that were accessible to policy makers and program
managers.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, a lot of high quality research work has
remained on the shelves or only available in excellent
international journals not readily available in Africa," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added the conference was an opportune moment for the African
region to prepare for a good African representation for the year
2000 Bangkok international conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference has drawn participants from non-governmental
organizations, donor agencies, governments, regional and
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the total investment for health research
amounted to about 56 billion U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 90 percent of this is spent on research into problems
that concerns only 10 percent of the world's population.
</P>
<P>
And only 10 percent of the funds are currently used to improve
the health of 90 percent of the world's population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
