<HEADLINE> Angola Exports 900 Cubic Meters of Black Granite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Angola has exported about 900
cubic meters of "black granite" for the first half of 1999, the
official news agency Angop reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The black granite, extracted from the mining zone of
Tchicuatite in southern Huila Province, has been exported to
countries in Europe, America and Asia, such as Portugal, Belgium,
Spain, Italy, the United States, China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The largest company in the mining zone Angostonem, which
established its first stone-pit in August 1998, has exported 500
cubic meters of black granite from January to June this year.
</P>
<P>
The company has reportedly invested two million U.S. dollars
this year in a bid to produce more black granite which has a ready
sale in the international market.
</P>
<P>
The Ango-Rochas Company, another big granite company in the
mining zone, has acquired advanced techniques and the production
of the black granite is expected to reach 150 cubic meters per
month, said Francisco Bernardino, general director of the company.
</P>
<P>
The companies have also engaged themselves in prospecting mines
of the red granite in the mining zone, which is in great demand in
the markets in Europe, America and Asia.
</P>
<P>
In each company, the Portuguese investors hold 70 percent of
the shares while the Angolan Ministry of Geology and Mines holds
30 percent. They have prospected 17,000 hectares of the
60,000-hectare mining zone in Tchicuatite. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
