<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Banks Raise Minimum Lending Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Two major commercial banks in
Zimbabwe announced Wednesday that they have hiked their minimum
lending rates to 56. 5 percent, threatening to put Zimbabweans
into another round of increases in borrowing rates.
</P>
<P>
The Commercial Bank of Zimbabwe and First Bank raised their
lending rates from 52.5 percent to 56.5 percent with effect from
September 21 and September 22 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Other major banks which charge interest rates of around 52
percent are expected to follow suit in the near future, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Money market analysts said that the moves were expected given
the inflationary pressures in the economy and the upward movement
in the 91-day treasury bill rate.
</P>
<P>
The treasury bill rate, which determines the movement of other
money market rates, shot up by two percentage points last week to
50.87 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Commercial Bank of Zimbabwe recommended that in such an
environment, short-term investment remains the best option as
banks are likely to revise upwards their lending rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
