<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan VP Calls for More Attention to Youth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Young people ... lack working skills and are prone to drugs,
smoking, violence and HIV/AIDS. So they are the most vulnerable
group in the society in a sense," the vice-president said in a
speech read at the official launching of the World Population
Report 1999 here on Wednesday evening..
</P>
<P>
In the speech read for her by Minister of General Duties in the
Prime Minister's Office Mondo Kagonyera, the vice-president urged
the government at both national and district levels as well as
non-governmental organizations to give more attention to youth.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has a population of 22.1 million people and about 80
percent are under the age of 30, according to the latest
information released by the Population Secretariat under the
Ugandan Ministry of Finance, Planning and Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
"The future challenges are too important to be left to the
government alone. We need participation of all interested
groups," said the vice- president.
</P>
<P>
Confessing that the government has a long way to go to
remarkably improve the quality of the youth's life, she reaffirmed
the government's commitment to continue to invest in education
programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
