<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Mulls Collective Intervention in Civil Wars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Defense Ministers of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) countries on
Wednesday called for a collective approach to intervention in wars
in the region.
</P>
<P>
The ministers, making the call at a two-day meeting in the
Swaziland capital of Mbabane, were seeking to clarify the SADC
approach to intervention in conflicts in any of its 14 member
states, Swazi Foreign Minister Albert Shabangu said in his opening
address.
</P>
<P>
The defense commanders of all SADC states attended the opening
session apart from those from the war-wracked nations of Angola
and the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), who were still
expected, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Shabangu, head of SADC's committee on interstate defense and
security, said peace and security were essential for economic
development in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Without peace and security, all the work in producing goods
would have been wasted," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shabangu said talks were under way to include foreign ministers
in discussions on a new protocol on intervention in conflicts in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The Mbabane meeting, due to end late Thursday, follows talks on
the protocol in Pretoria on Monday between Shabangu and the
defense ministers of South Africa and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, South Africa and Botswana on behalf of SADC launched a
joint military intervention in the troubled kingdom of Lesotho to
quell a coup.
</P>
<P>
Later in the year, several SADC states were intervening in the
DRC, taking sides with different parties in the conflict after the
Tutsi-led rebels launched an uprising against the government of
President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
All parties to that conflict have signed a ceasefire accord,
but sporadic fighting is still being reported.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0021 </DOCNO>
