<HEADLINE> Italy Calls EU Integration on Balkan's Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Isolating Serbia and Belgrade
from reconstruction efforts will not serve any purpose, Italian
Foreign Trade Minister Piero Fassino said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an international convention on reconstruction in
the Balkans in Italy's south city of Ancona, Fassino underlined
that the international community should not exclude Serbia from
reconstruction efforts.
</P>
<P>
"Isolating Serbia and Belgrade from reconstruction efforts will
not serve any purpose," he said, adding that "the international
community's policy should therefore be to maintain relations while
pressing for change."
</P>
<P>
"The only way to bring peace and stability to the region is the
prospect of European integration bringing the Balkans closer to
the European Union," Fassino said.
</P>
<P>
The matter of European integration, one of the "pillars for
stability" cannot, however, be resolved in two or three years,
Fassino said.
</P>
<P>
"It will be a long process, especially since the various phases
of EU enlargement have already been defined," the minister said,
adding, "it is important, however, to lay out our objectives."
</P>
<P>
It is also important that efforts to re-build the economy in
the region should continue, Fassino said.
</P>
<P>
"Economic reconstruction will lead to social and moral
reconstruction, it will help heal the country's awful wounds,
which were opened up by the war," the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
