<HEADLINE> Global Population to Reach 6 Billion on October 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The world's population will
reach 6 billion on October 12 this year, a U.N. official predicted
here Wednesday, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Nizamuddin, of the U.N.'s Population Foundation, said
the population will have grown by 1 billion in just 12 years.
People younger than 25 will make-up nearly one-half of the
population and the 15-24 age group alone will total 1 billion.
</P>
<P>
By 2050, Nizamuddin said, the earth's population may increase
to 8.9 billion, Interfax said, quoting an annual Population Fund
report.
</P>
<P>
One-fifth of the population suffer from malnutrition and
shortage of protein, 2 billion are anemic, one-third of the
population has no access to running water, modern medical services
are not available to one-fifth of the population. Nearly 20
percent of the world's children do not attend primary schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
