<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Hold Talks with Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa have held talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton on
bilateral and multilateral issues at the United Nations
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The talks were "cordial and very fruitful," according to a
report by Mkapa's press secretary Geoffrey Nkurlu from New York
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents held the talks Tuesday after both had
addressed the U. N. General Assembly to articulate their positions
on matters facing their countries and the international community.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, who is on a working visit to the United States, flew to
Atlanta, Georgia Wednesday morning and later visited the CNN
center.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian President will receive an honorary Ph.D. degree
Thursday at Morehouse University College and is scheduled to visit
former U.S. President Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
He also plans to visit the Martin Luther King Center that is
based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
The delegation led by Mkapa includes Minister of Foreign
Affairs and International Co-operation, Jakaya Kikwete, Zanzibar's
Minister of Communication and Transport, Amani Karume, as well as
investment and economic reform officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
