<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Denktash to Pay Political Price if Refuses Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Government Spokesman
Michalis Papapetrou said in New York Wednesday that Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash would pay political price if he
refuses to take part in talks over the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides, who is on a visit in the
United States, and the U.S. Presidential envoy for Cyprus Alfred
Moses discussed Wednesday the preparations for a new round of
talks aimed at a solution to the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou, who was accompanying the president, told reporters
after the meeting that the meeting "did not focus only on
procedural issues, but rather on issues which would secure the
success of the talks, if they take place."
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the U.S. has put forward any proposals,
Papapetrou said "there was an exchange of views on all issues
including the basic aspects of the Cyprus issue."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. believes that United Nations Secretary General Kofi
Annan is committed by U.N. Security Council resolutions to send
invitations to the two sides in Cyprus for talks, he added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the international community has been trying to
bring the two sides to negotiate for reunification through a
bicommunal settlement. But no tangible progress has been achieved.
</P>
<P>
The seven most industrialized nations plus Russia (G-8), in
their June summit in Cologne, Germany, asked the U.N. chief to
invite leaders of the two communities to unconditional
negotiations in the fall of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Clerides has said he expects to be invited to talks in the
second half of October.
</P>
<P>
However, the prospect of holding such meetings remains gloomy
as Denktash insists that he would not enter into negotiations
unless his breakaway state in northern Cyprus, recognized only by
Turkey, be internationally recognized and talk with Nicosia on
equal basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
