<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNFPA Urges to Improve Human Living Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Population Fund (UNFPA) Wednesday urged peoples of the world to
make efforts to improve their lives when the new millenium comes.
</P>
<P>
The New York-based UNFPA, which was established in 1966, made
the appeal here at the launching of the 1999 State of the World
Population Report with a theme "A Time for Choices".
</P>
<P>
The UN agency said the fate of the world population largely
depends on the decision and action taken in the next decade,
particularly on actions to increase education, promote gender
equality and ensure the universal exercise of the right to health.
</P>
<P>
The world population has passed the six billion mark, rising by
about 78 million a year, according to the UNFPA.
</P>
<P>
More than one billion people are still deprived of basic needs
while one third have no access to clean water and one fifth to
modern health services.
</P>
<P>
Despite progress on women's health and lives, hundreds of
millions of women continue to suffer from gender-based violence,
unwanted pregnancy, unsafe abortion and ill health, the UNFPA
said.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Ethiopian government, the UNFPA and
pertinent non- government organizations attended the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The "Day of Six Billion" population will be observed on October
12 this year, organizers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
