<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Life Expectancy Falls in  Africa Due to High AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Prevalence
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Life expectancy in the
African continent is suffering heavily from the AIDS pandemic,
the leading cause of death in the continent and the fourth most
common cause of death worldwide.
</P>
<P>
"In demographic terms, the future effect of AIDS is likely to
be relatively limited on the global scale, but it will have a
devastating impact on several African countries," according to
the World Population Report 1999 launched Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that out of the 34 countries most affected by
HIV/AIDS, 29 are in Africa. The average life expectancy at birth
in these countries is currently seven years less than it would
have been in the absence of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
"In Botswana, with the world's highest HIV/AIDS prevalence
rates, one of every four adults is infected and the life
expectancy has fallen from 61 in the late 1980s to 47 today," the
76-page report pointed out.
</P>
<P>
In Zimbabwe, the second-hardest-hit country, one in five
adults is infected. Estimated life expectancy at birth is 44
years and will fall to 41 in 2000-2005, 25 years less than what
would be expected in the absence of the killer disease.
</P>
<P>
There are roughly 33.4 million people who are HIV positive in
the world now, 70 percent of whom are living in Africa. The
pandemic has a terrible effect on individuals and communities, as
it strikes down working people, orphans children and places huge
strains on health care and social systems.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
