<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Continues Efforts for Debt Cancellation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A 100-day long debt
cancellation campaign in Zambia will focus on advocacy by
continuing to collect signatures to add to the 300,000 that have
already been collected.
</P>
<P>
Jack Zulu, national coordinator Jubilee 2000 Zambia, said here
 Wednesday that the Zambian debt project had renewed its efforts
to make debt cancellation a reality before the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Jubilee 2000 is an international debt cancellation campaign
aiming to provide hope for the indebted millions around the world.
</P>
<P>
Zulu said the debt cancellation project in Zambia will also
carry out educational campaigns targeted at schools, churches,
non-governmental organizations and all other concerned
individuals.
</P>
<P>
It will also engage in research to try and find out mechanisms
for guaranteeing that any resources freed from that are
accountable and effective.
</P>
<P>
Without debt cancellation poor countries worldwide would not
experience any sustainable development as reflected by the United
Nations Development Program (UNDP) report, said Zulu.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, everyone of the 10 million Zambians owes
650 U.S. dollars to international creditors.
</P>
<P>
According to a human development report released by the UNDP,
sub- Saharan African countries are at the bottom of human
development index.
</P>
<P>
About 260 million people in the region are subsisting on less
than one dollar per day.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a large debt burden motivates a lot of poor
countries to lower labor standards as they engage in a desperate
struggle to attract foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The worldwide anti-debt campaign, organized by the Jubilee 2000
group, is underway to lobby donor countries and international
lending institutions to cancel the unpayable debt for the
impoverished countries of the world by the next millennium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Futures Rises as OPEC Sticks to Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Crude oil futures rose on
Wednesday after first stumbling slightly as the markets responded
to mixed signals over increasing U.S. crude stocks and the message
from OPEC ministers that output cuts were to stay.
</P>
<P>
Benchmark Brent blend crude abandoned early gains after the
Energy Information Administration (EIA) caught the market off
guard with news of U.S. crude reserves actually rose last week
rather than fell, as previously thought, according to a Reuters
report.
</P>
<P>
But the November contract swiftly recovered to trade 22 cents
higher at 22.90 U.S. dollars a barrel as OPEC President and
Algerian Oil Minister Youssef Yousfi told the cartel's
policy-making conference in Vienna that the oil market remained
fragile and stocks high.
</P>
<P>
The EIA said U.S. crude stockpiles rose by 200,000 barrels last
week, contradicting earlier American Petroleum Institute figures
which pointed to a substantial fall in reserves to near two-year
lows.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the high EIA figure caused short-term jitters as
the market considered the impact of OPEC's supply curbs on the
world's biggest oil consumer, but was soon overshadowed by
reassuring comments from Vienna.
</P>
<P>
"(Brent) came off after the EIA numbers but then it bounced
right back up...Everyone's forgotten about (the stocks data) now,"
Reuters quoted one broker as saying. "We're just watching out for
OPEC now."
</P>
<P>
Yousfi noted that equilibrium between supply and demand was
only just beginning to emerge, saying: "This assessment also shows
that there is no shortage of oil in the market, and that stock
levels are still high and could,at any time, have a negative
impact on prices."
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that with the continuation of the same high
degree of compliance by member countries witnessed to date, up to
March 2000, we shall attain a better and more sustainable
equilibrium," he was quoted as telling oil ministers.
</P>
<P>
World oil prices have more than doubled this year since OPEC
introduced supply curbs and began holding back 4.3 million barrels
a day. But ministers want to be sure last year's oil glut, which
dragged prices below 10 U.S. dollars a barrel, has dried up
reliably before relaxing the curbs, due to run through until the
end of March 2000.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts have predicted a supply shortfall in the northern
hemisphere winter months as a result of the OPEC cuts, which could
push prices too high and subsequently stunt demand growth. But
OPEC seemed content to allow prices to rise further to help
restore member states' shrivelled revenues, Reuters said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Says World Economic Situation Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund released the World Economic Outlook here today, predicting a
global economic growth of about 3 percent in 1999, 0.7 percent
higher than that projected in May this year. The global growth
rate for 2000 would be 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Global economic and financial conditions have improved markedly
after the turbulence in emerging markets in 1997-98, which gave
rise to fears of a widespread credit crunch and global recession,
and most of the economies recently in crisis have begun to
recover, said the IMF report.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that financial market confidence has
been returning in most of the emerging market economies affected
by the crisis, allowing monetary conditions to ease and setting
the stage for economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
For all the Asian crisis economies, growth projections for 1999
have been revised up significantly, and the economic overturns in
Brazil and Russia have been shallower that expected earlier, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices have recovered, and declines in many other commodity
prices have been arrested, providing relief for some
commodity-exporting countries affected by the ripple effects of
the slowdown.
</P>
<P>
There has also been an upward revision of growth in Japan,
where there was a significant rise in activity in the first half
of 1999 following the steep contraction during 1997-98,. And the
projected strengthening of growth in Europe seems to be
materializing, while the impressive U.S. expansion has continued,
amid few signs of emerging price or wage pressures.
</P>
<P>
Global growth appears to have bottomed out at 2.5 percent in
1998, in what the projections suggest will have been the mildest
of the four slowdowns in the world economy in the past three
decades, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Economic Outlook projections, Advanced
economies will grow 2.8 percent and 2.7 percent respectively in
1999 and 2000, 0.8 percent and 0.4 percent higher respectively
that the figure projected in May.
</P>
<P>
Economies of the developing countries will grow 3.5 percent and
4.8 percent in 1999 and 2000 respectively, 0.4 percent higher and
0.1 percent lower than predicted earlier. China's economic growth
is predicted to be 6.6 percent and 6.0 percent in 1999 and 2000
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Countries in transition such as Russia will grow 0.8 percent
and 2.8 percent in 1999 and 2000 respectively, 1.7 percent and 0.3
percent higher than earlier projected.
</P>
<P>
However, the report cautioned that many challenges remain to be
addressed to ensure that these recoveries are sustainable, and to
foster stronger and more stable growth in the world economy in the
next decade.
</P>
<P>
There is particular reason for concern about the unbalanced
pattern of growth observed recently among the major industrial
countries and about the economic and financial consequences
worldwide if the eventual demand slowdown in the United States
turns out to be sharper than is generally expected at present.
</P>
<P>
While the return to broad price stability remains an important
policy achievement, macroeconomic instability has persisted in
much of the world economy, continuing to pose challenges for, and
in many ways making new demands on, economic policies.
</P>
<P>
If growth were to weaken significantly in the U.S. without
offsets in Japan and Europe, there would also be reason for
concern about the sustainability of the recoveries underway in the
Asian economies recently in crisis, and much of Latin America
would be particularly vulnerable under such a scenario.
</P>
<P>
An additional risk factor relates to potential financial
market reactions to actual or perceived Y2K compliance problems
in emerging market, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
