<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Approves Defense Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Wednesday
voted 93-5 to pass the nation's defense bill for the fiscal year
2001.
</P>
<P>
The 288.9-billion-U.S.-dollar bill includes a military pay
raise and a 4.4 percent across-the-board increase in Defense
Department spending, including more money for military housing and
hardware.
</P>
<P>
The House approved the measure on a 375-45 vote last week, and
the bill was sent to U.S. President Bill Clinton for his
signature.
</P>
<P>
The defense bill authorizes the full 1.8 billion U.S. dollars
for production of six supersonic, radar-evading F-22 warplanes. A
separate House spending bill endorsed cutting those funds, and the
issue was to be taken up by a joint House-Senate negotiating
committee later Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
