<HEADLINE> Thailand Personnel Sent to Discuss East Timor Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A group of Thai military
personnel has been sent to Australia to discuss and decide areas
where Thai peacekeepers will be in charge in East Timor, Supreme
Commander of Thai Armed Forces General Mongkon Ampornpisit said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A five-member team of Thai strategic planners flew to Canberra
to coordinate and work out for Thailand's assigned areas with
other countries taking part in the United Nation-led peacekeeping
force in East Timor, or Interfet.
</P>
<P>
A batch of Thai peacekeepers will then be sent to the territory
next month after the strategic planners reach agreement with other
parties over the responsible areas, Mongkon said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, General Songkit Chakkabat and 33 members of the
76-strong advance team have returned from East Timor from a
preparation trip there.
</P>
<P>
Songkit, who is also Interfet's deputy commander, reported to
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai that the team had met with other
advance teams from 15 countries in Darwin, Australia, before
traveling to Dili, the capital of East Timor, and Baucau, a small
town located 100 kilometers east of Dili.
</P>
<P>
He said his team was welcomed by Indonesian troops, and "the
geographic survey with good cooperation from the Indonesian
military has achieved a set goal, ensuing anticipated
accomplishment of the Thai mission in East Timor."
</P>
<P>
Bloody violence has erupted in East Timor after a majority of
its people voted for independence from Indonesia on August 30,
prompting the international community to pool troops and
assistance to help return the territory back to peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
