<HEADLINE> Over Half Million Tanzanians Suffering from AIDS: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 22 (Xinhua) -- More than half a
million people in his country are suffering from AIDS, a Tanzanian
minister said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State Edward Lowassa said that although only
109,863 AIDS cases are reported, it is estimated that over 550,000
are already suffering from the deadly disease in the east African
country.
</P>
<P>
When launching the State of World Population 1999 Report,
Lowassa said that over 1.5 million Tanzanians are infected with
HIV, the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The minister compared the figures to those of neighboring
Uganda where 1. 9 million people are HIV positive while there are
500,000 reported AIDS cases.
</P>
<P>
At present, the HIV status of blood donors in Tanzania stands
at 10 percent, compared with five percent ten years ago, Lowassa
said.
</P>
<P>
He said Tanzania has 300,000 children orphaned by victims of
HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony of launching the population report, Teferi
Seyoum, representative of the United Nations Population Fund
(UNFPA), said that the worldwide new HIV/AIDS infections count 11
a minute, more than 15,000 a day and more than 5.7 million a year.
</P>
<P>
Over half of those infected are young people below the age of
24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
