<HEADLINE> Egypt, India to Cooperate in Computer Software </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and India on Wednesday
signed a memorandum of understanding aimed at bolstering
cooperation in upgrading Egypt's software industry.
</P>
<P>
The memo was inked by the General Arab Organization and the
Social Fund for Development (SFD) on the Egyptian side and the
Bae-Hal-and-Bel Foundation for India, Egypt's Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Indian foundation is specialized in developing computer
software, programs, and manufacturing electronics and spare parts
of computer hardware.
</P>
<P>
The memo came as a quick response to Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak's call on state institutions to work out plans of action
to upgrade Egypt's software industry, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Under the memorandum, the General Arab Organization will set up
an advanced training center with the help of the Indian foundation
to train professional programmers and, meanwhile, manufacture
low-cost personal computers.
</P>
<P>
Salah Halabi, head of the organization, said at the signing
ceremony that his organization plans to establish an international
consultancy house for programming.
</P>
<P>
Halabi said the organization focuses on developing high-tech
industries.
</P>
<P>
SFD Secretary General Hussein el-Gamal said the Indian
foundation will transfer expertise to the fund to help upgrade
Egyptian medium- and small-sized projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
