<HEADLINE> EU, Zimbabwe Hold Talks on Fund Disbursement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and
the Zimbabwean Ministry of Finance are expected to come up with a
framework that will assist in the disbursement of 34 million U.S.
dollars to help the economic reforms in the southern African
country.
</P>
<P>
EU economic adviser Jose Leandro said here Wednesday that the
two sides are holding technical discussions ahead of the release
of the fund.
</P>
<P>
"We are not setting up new conditions but merely looking at
issues within the general framework under the action plan program
which was adopted by the (Zimbabwean) government for its economic
reforms," the Zimbabwe News Agency quoted Leandro as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that the government is doing all it can to
implement measures set by the IMF (International Monetary Fund)
for its economic reforms," the EU official said.
</P>
<P>
He said the EU was also waiting to see Harare's commitment to
education and health especially when it came to budget
allocations.
</P>
<P>
The talks come a month after the IMF released a 193
million-dollar balance of payment support to Zimbabwe and signed
an agreement with Harare to implement a program to stabilize the
macro-economic environment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Leandro said EU's board would meet in December to
decide on the release of a 11.4-million-Euro support to Zimbabwe's
educational sector.
</P>
<P>
The EU recently approved 5.2 million dollars in support of the
Zimbabwean land reform program following a land donor conference
held in Harare last year. 
</P>
