<HEADLINE> Lebanese Officials' Phones Tapped: House Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese House Speaker Nabih
Berri Wednesday renewed his accusation that the country's
officials' phones are being tapped.
</P>
<P>
"The phone tapping is being conducted for purpose of security,
politics and judiciary and need to be legalized in a mechanism
which can make the practice serve the country's security rather
than infringe on public freedom," he told local guests.
</P>
<P>
His claim came in the wake of a parliamentary investigation
into telephone tapping, which sparked a controversy last week
after contradictory statements by Interior Minister Michel Murr
and intelligence officials.
</P>
<P>
Murr denied authorities were tapping Lebanese phones, while the
head of the General Security Services, Brigadier General Jamil
Sayed, told parliament last week there was tapping.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Lebanese former Defense Minister Mohsen Dalloul
threw another heavy bombshell on the issue by accusing the United
States of having a spy station near the Lebanese Defense Ministry
and presidential palace on the eastern edge of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
He said the surveillance equipment had long been used by the
U.S. for regional monitoring to serve Israel's interests.
</P>
<P>
His statements prompted his successor Ghazi Zuetir and the
judiciary to demand immediate clarifications, although the
U.S. embassy in Beirut has declined to make any comments on it.
</P>
<P>
Dalloul added he was prepared to accompany Zuetir to
investigate the purported location of the equipment. 
</P>
