<HEADLINE> UK Expert Warns of Human "Mad Cow" Disease Epidemic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Britain could face an epidemic
of human "mad cow" disease in the years ahead, with the cases
possibly running to thousands and the true scale of the problem
not known for 15 years, Britain's chief medical officer has
warned.
</P>
<P>
In a report to British Agriculture Minister Nick Brown,
Professor Liam Donaldson, British government's chief medical
adviser, said the number of cases of new variant of CJD
(Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease), the human form of "mad cow" disease,
could range from a few hundred to many thousand.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, first cases of the new variant of CJD
in Britain had been identified three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Up to the end of June 1999, the total number of people who had
died from the disease was 43. In 1998 alone, 16 people died, a 60
percent increase on 1997, when there were 10 deaths.
</P>
<P>
"What is absolutely certain is that the present relatively low
number of CJD (cases) should not lead anyone to conclude that the
worst is over," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Also in the report, Professor Donaldson said the risk of
catching CJD from eating beef-on-the-bone is "tiny and
unquantifiable" and recommended the lifting of the
beef-on-the-bone ban which has been in place since December 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, some British scientists disagreed with Professor
Donaldson' prediction, saying that speculation about a CJD
epidemic is "alarmist".
</P>
<P>
Researchers from City University said that they believed there
will be a decline in CJD deaths after this year and these will be
over by 2006.
</P>
<P>
"The total number of (CJD) deaths ever could be as low as 75",
they said Wednesday in a statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
