<HEADLINE> Palestinian Hardline Faction to Join Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A senior member of the
Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine (DFLP), a
Palestinian hard-line faction, said Wednesday the DFLP has decided
to join the peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Taysir Khaled, member of the DFLP political bureau, said the
group made the decision after its leader Nayyef Hawatmeh met
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in Cairo, Egypt recently.
</P>
<P>
Hawatmeh, who runs the DFLP from Damascus, Syria, has said he
would like to return to the West Bank and Gaza. Israel said last
week that there will be no problem for Hawatmeh's return to the
territories since the DFLP leader has not participated in any
terrorist activities against Israel.
</P>
<P>
The DFLP would take part in a Palestinian leadership meeting
about the peace talks, and would decide then on its level of
participation in the negotiations, Khaled said.
</P>
<P>
DFLP's decision to take part in the peace talks reflects
efforts made by Arafat to rally more support from Palestinian
factions in peace negotiations with Israel, beyond his own Fatah
movement.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians launched their final-status talks
on September 13.
</P>
<P>
Under the new peace deal signed by Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Arafat in Egyptian Red Sea resort of Sharm El Sheikh
earlier this month, the two sides have to work out a framework
agreement on final-status talks by February and a full lasting
treaty by September 2000.
</P>
<P>
The DFLP and the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine,
or PFLP, have stayed out of peace-making process with Israel so
far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
