<HEADLINE> U.S. Justice Department Sues tobacco Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Justice Department
filed a lawsuit against eight major tobacco companies Wednesday to
recover billions of dollars taxpayers have spent on
smoking-related illnesses, Attorney General Janet Reno announced.
</P>
<P>
"In the complaint, the United States alleges that for the past
45 years, the companies that manufacture and sell tobacco have
waged an intentional and coordinated campaign of deceit," Reno
told a news conference in announcing the civil lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
She says the campaign has been aimed at preserving what she
calls the "enormous profits" of the companies -- no matter what
the cost would be in human lives, human suffering and medical
resources.
</P>
<P>
The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court here, alleges that
the cigarette companies conspired since the 1950s to defraud and
mislead the American public and to conceal information about the
effects of smoking.
</P>
<P>
The eight companies are Philip Morris Inc., Philip Morris
Companies, R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., American Tobacco Co., Brown
$ Williamson Tobacco Co. Inc., Liggett and Myers Inc., The Council
for Tobacco Research U.S.A. Inc. and the Tobacco Institute Inc.
</P>
<P>
"Smoking is the nation's largest preventable cause of death and
disease, and American taxpayers should not have to bear the
responsibility for the staggering costs," she said.
</P>
<P>
"We filed a lawsuit that seeks to recover from the tobacco
companies the billions of dollars that American taxpayers spend
each year on tobacco-related illnesses," she said. ``On behalf of
the taxpayers, we are asking the tobacco companies to pay their
fair share."
</P>
<P>
Reno said the aim of the lawsuit is to "require the tobacco
companies to restore the funds that they acquired through their
unlawful conduct.... I pledge today that we will work tirelessly
to see that justice is done."
</P>
<P>
"The Justice Department is taking the right course of action:
It is time for America's taxpayers to have their day in court,"
President Bill Clinton said in a statement after the suit was
filed.
</P>
<P>
The American Lung Association, in a quick response to welcome
the lawsuit, said tobacco companies must be held accountable for
the death, disease and economic burdens caused by their products.
</P>
<P>
"The federal government now spends an estimated 22 billion
dollars each year on smoking-related illnesses," the association
said. "More than half of it is paid by Medicare. For too long,
these costs have been unfairly borne by U.S. taxpayers."
</P>
<P>
The lawsuit poses a major new legal threat to the tobacco
industry, which has already been faced with lawsuits filed by
states and individual smokers in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's lawsuit was a new setback for the tobacco industry
which agreed in November 1998 to pay 46 states 206 billion dollars
in a broad deal to treat smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
The tobacco industry has strongly questioned the government's
authority to bring such a lawsuit, saying the lawsuit was
"legally meritless" and would fail in court.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's 1st Domestic-Made Super Generator Operational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China's first domestic-made
550,000 kilowatt hydropower generating unit went into formal
operation today at the Ertan Hydropower Station in southwest China
's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
The unit, jointly produced by the Harbin Electrical Machinery
Works in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province and the Shanghai-
based Dongfang Electrical Machinery Works, is the fifth generating
unit that has gone into formal operation at the Ertan power plant
near Panzhihua city.
</P>
<P>
The power plant, designed with six 550,000 kilowatt generating
units, would be the largest hydropower plant in China when the
last unit goes into operation at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Ertan is also China's first hydropower plant to be built
through international bidding.
</P>
<P>
Canada's General Electric Co.(GE) won the contract for the
manufacture of the six generating units through the bidding, but
according to the contract, it would only independently produce the
first two units, while the third and fourth would be a joint
project of GE and the Harbin and Shanghai firms, and the fifth and
sixth would be produced by the Chinese firms alone.
</P>
<P>
Before this project, the most powerful hydropower generating
unit produced by China had the capacity of 320,000 kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
The Ertan power plant has produced 3.9 billion kilowatt hours
of power since August 1998, when its first generating unit went
into operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
