<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Trade Delegation to Visit Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A group of more than 50
delegates from British oil, gas, construction and engineering
companies are scheduled to visit Libya next month to forge
business contracts from renewed political goodwill.
</P>
<P>
It will be the biggest British trade mission to Libya since
diplomatic ties between the two countries were broken off 15 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
"The trade mission could not be better timed. Libya is in the
process of enjoying an economic renaissance and is actively
seeking out business partners to explore the possibilities of
joint venture," Jeremy Hanley, the trade mission's co-leader, said
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The planned trip, from October 3-7, comes less than three
months after the two countries announced they were resuming
diplomatic relations when Tripoli agreed to cooperate in
investigations into the death of a British police-woman in 1984.
</P>
<P>
The police-woman, Yvonne Fletcher, was shot to death outside
Libya's embassy in London. Her death strongly effected the
relation between Libya and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Four years after the death of Fletcher, a Pan-AM airliner was
bombed over the Scottish town of Lockerbie, killing 270 people.
Britain and the United States accused two Libyan agents of
responsibility to the bombing and requested Libya to send them to
Britain to face trial.
</P>
<P>
After the request was rejected, Britain cut all its political
contact with Libya.
</P>
<P>
In April, Libya handed over the two suspects, opening the way
for Britain to discuss resuming ties.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Libya's energy sector was top of the list
of investment opportunities for British businessmen who are going
to Libya next month.
</P>
<P>
Delegates would also be looking at investing in the final
stages of Libya's giant "man-made river" which pipes water
hundreds of kilometers from desert aquifers to its parched
Mediterranean cities.
</P>
<P>
Libya's tourism, railways and airports could also be targets
for British investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
