<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weak Baht Good for Thai Exports: Deputy PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government saw no
need to intervene in the market to support the sliding baht as a
weak currency could help exports, Deputy Prime Minister and
Commerce Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Supachai told reporters that the government was not concerned
with the temporarily weak baht, as the currency had been
stabilized and the Thai economy had been steadily recovering.
</P>
<P>
"The temporary fluctuation of the baht results from both
external and internal factors, which are believed to last long,"
Supachai said.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the baht's losses partly to the
lower-than-expected 3.5 percent year-on-year growth of the Thai
gross domestic product for the second quarter of 1999, compared
with an earlier market expectation of up to 8 percent. Fluctuation
of the Japanese yen was also seen as a factor for the weakening of
the Thai currency.
</P>
<P>
Thai baht moved to a new year-low of 40.40 to the dollar on
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
