<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Head of Iran's Chamber of Commerce, Industries and
Mines Ali-Naqi Khamoushi said on Wednesday the Iranian government
has insured all foreign investments in Iran and and the foreign
investors are allowed to transfer their capital and interests at
any time they wish to.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the Iranian law concerning foreign
investments in Iran has set no limitation on the private sector's
operation and foreign investors have the right to possess 99
percent of the enterprises.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has also improved tax payment methods
including taxation on the salaries of foreign workers in Iran.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Minister of Housing and Urban Development Ail
Abdolalizadeh expressed in Rome Tuesday Iran's readiness for
formation of joint ventures with Italian firms in order to promote
the quality and quantity of house building and its technology in
Iran.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the good performance of Iranian construction firms
in other countries, the central Asian region in particular, the
minister called for Tehran-Rome construction cooperation in third
countries.
</P>
<P>
Confirming the technical achievements of Iran in the field of
construction materials, the vice-president of Italian constructors
association expressed Italian firms' readiness to cooperate with
Iran in housing sector.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Spanish government Wednesday offered a loan of 60
million U.S. dollars to Turkey for reconstruction in the
quake-stricken Marmara region, said a Spanish statement here.
</P>
<P>
The statement issued by the Spanish Embassy in Ankara said
that the loan would be interest-free and have a 30-year maturity.
</P>
<P>
The statement added that the Spanish government was ready
for cooperation with the concerned Turkish authorities for the
best use of that loan.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Bank of Israel reports that the combined
economic index for August rose by 1 percent, following a rise of
0.6 percent in July, reflecting the recent increase in economic
activity.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Consumer Price Index rose 0.5 percent in
August, reaching 105.6 points. In the first eight months of 1999,
the CPI has risen by 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's national telecommunication company Bezeq
has filed a 19 million dollars lawsuit against the U.S. company
AMS Technical System over an agreement signed two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Bezeq claimed that the AMS did not meet its commitments made in
the agreement, according to which the AMS would develop, supply
and install computerized billing systems for Bezeq customers. It
demanded that the AMS return the money it had handed over and
make compensation according to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel will explore the possibility of importing
heavy crude oil from Venezuela, according to agreement reached by
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela's Trade Minister Juan Deguizas Montier made the
proposal for Israel to acquire large quantities of heavy crude
oil and coal during his recent visit to Israel, also offered
to supply natural gas.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Although industrial exports have been slowly
rising up in recent months, a survey of leading export companies
in Israel showed that industrial exports have grown by only 3
percent so far in 1999, the slowest pace of growth posted in eight
years.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the main factor holding down exports was growing
competition in the target markets. They said the survey
demonstrates that Israeli industry has yet to claim success in
joining the process of globalization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
