<HEADLINE> Britain Announces Permanent Memorial to Diana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair said on Wednesday that Britain would build a permanent
memorial to late Princess Diana.
</P>
<P>
He announced his decision in the mass circulation Mirror
newspaper, which said the memorial would take the form of a
fountain in one of London's royal parks.
</P>
<P>
"There will be a permanent memorial to Princess Diana," Blair
said. "It is very important that we honour the memory of someone
who not only was very dear to people in this country but also
achieved a lot."
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman said any plans would be made in
consultation with the Royal family, while there would also be
talks with the Royal Parks over a site for the memorial.
</P>
<P>
Diana's brother, Earl Spencer and Diana's mother, Frances Shand
Kydd, backed the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Britain's chancellor of the exchequer, Gordon Brown, chairman
of the Princess Diana Memorial Committee, said in a statement that
he would consult the princess's family about the planned memorial.
</P>
<P>
The Diana, Princess of Wales Memorial Committee has considered
proposals for a fountain in Kensington Gardens. The Princess lived
at Kensington Palace after her marriage to Prince Charles
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
Fans of Diana have long been urging Britain to build a memorial
to the princess, who died in a Paris car crash in August 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
