<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan President to Attend U.N. Meetings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President
Chandrika Bandaranaike Kumaratunga will leave for New York on
Saturday to attend the last historic session of the United Nations
General Assembly, the Government Information Department said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The department said in a statement that the president, who is
also the finance minister, will also attend the annual meetings of
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
She will also have discussions with U.S. officials especially
on the issue of separatist Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE)
in the aftermath of the Amparai massacre, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE guerrillas, fighting the government since 1983 for a
separate homeland in Sri Lanka's north and east, have been blamed
for last weekend's massacre of over 50 civilians in the southeast
of the country.
</P>
<P>
The attacks followed LTTE accusations that Sri Lanka's Air
Force had killed 22 Tamil refugees in airstrikes on a village in
the northeast.
</P>
<P>
The United States designated the LTTE as a foreign terrorist
organization in October 1997, banning its fund-raising on the
soils of the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said Mrs. Kumaratunga will also use the
visit to seek support for Sri Lanka's bid to get the top post of
the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO) for its candidate Senaka Bandaranayake.
</P>
</TEXT>
