<HEADLINE> AIDS Leads to 200,000 Orphans in S. African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- About 200,000 children
under the age of 15 will be orphaned due to the affection of
HIV/AIDS in South Africa' s KwaZulu-Natal Province by the year
2000, the National Assembly's welfare committee heard Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a presentation on the implications of HIV/AIDS, Mary Caesar,
national coordinator of the AIDS Legal Network, said about 75
percent of hospital beds in the province were currently occupied
by children suffering from the disease.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that 12,000 children throughout the country
were already HIV positive, she said.
</P>
<P>
Children in affected households might not be infected, but the
disease would have negative impact on them before and after the
death of their parents because they would have to leave school and
get jobs to supplement household income.
</P>
<P>
She said the death of a parent would also have a psychological
effect because the child would be deprived of love.
</P>
<P>
Sian Hasewinkel, a social worker with Cape Town Child Welfare,
said in an article published by South African Press Association
Wednesday that her organization had started a program to make
people realize that AIDS was not just an adult disease and to
mobilize partnerships between government, business, service
providers and communities.
</P>
<P>
She said strengthening families' capacity to cope with the
disease was important.
</P>
<P>
Community-based day care needed to be linked with health so
that children could be overseen on a number of levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
