<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges Peaceful Settlement of International </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China on Wednesday
called for peaceful settlement of international disputes.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the general debate of the 54th session of the United
Nations General Assembly, Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan
said the principle of the peaceful settlement of international
disputes initiated by the Hague Peace Conference held 100 years
ago is now an important principle of the U.N. Charter and a basic
principle of contemporary international law.
</P>
<P>
Tang said in the current international situation, adherence to
the principle of peaceful settlement of international disputes is
still of major immediate significance.
</P>
<P>
Peaceful settlement of international disputes is predicted on
the non-use and non-threat of force in international relations,
and China maintained that to handle state-to-state relations with
mentality of "hot war", "cold war", "power politics" or "bloc
politics" would get nowhere, he said.
</P>
<P>
All international disputes and regional conflicts should be
resolved justly and fairly through peaceful negotiation and
consultation on the basis of equality, rather by arbitrary use or
threat of force on strength of military superiority, he said.
</P>
<P>
Only in this way can there be a fundamental solution to
disputes or conflicts without complicating or aggravating them or
leaving a hidden peril behind, and only in this way can state
co-exist in harmony and attain common prosperity, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
