<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China on UN Role And Authority of Security Council (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The role of the United
Nations is indispensable to the achievement of genuine peace and
development and to the establishment of a just and reasonable new
international order, China said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the general debate of the 54th session of the United
Nations General Assembly, Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan
said to strengthen the role of U.N. goes with the historical
trend, meets the needs of the times and conforms to the shared
aspiration of all people in the world.
</P>
<P>
In order to strengthen the role of U.N., efforts should first
be made to uphold the sanctity of the purposes and principles of
the U.N. Charter, and the most important reason for which the U.N.
has been able to grow from 51 founding members to its current size
is that it has acted according to these purposes and principles,
Tang said.
</P>
<P>
It is the view of the Chinese Government that despite the great
changes that have taken place in the international situation, the
purposes and principles of the United Nations Charter are still
relevant, and China is opposed to any irresponsible interpretation
or revision of them, under whatever excuses, he said.
</P>
<P>
If the role of U.N. is to be strengthened, the authority of the
Security Council must be preserved, and any act to weaken this
authority or to impose the will of an individual country or a
group of countries on the Security Council is very dangerous, and
will further breed power politics and hegemonism and give rise to
endless troubles, he said.
</P>
<P>
If the U.N. role to be strengthened, it is essential to ensure
to all member states the rights to equal participation in
international affairs, so that their reasonable propositions will
be fully reflected and their legitimate rights and interests
protected by the U.N, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
Decisions made by the UN must give expression to the common
will of the majority of its members, and any attempt by a few
countries or a group of countries to monopolize world affairs and
decide the destiny of the people of other countries goes against
the trend of the times and will never succeed, he stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
