<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Supports Educational Reform in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) announced Wednesday the approval of a loan
of 36 million U.S. dollars to Colombia to initiate an educational
reform process.
</P>
<P>
The reform process aims to strengthen decentralized, autonomous
management of schools, improve efficiency and social equity in the
allocation of resources, and to improve quality of educational
services. It will also ensure that students in participating
schools are offered the full cycle of basic education, grades one
to nine. It will also ensure access to transparent information and
performance evaluations and promote citizens's participation in
the school system, the Washington-based IDB said.
</P>
<P>
As a demonstration, during these initial steps in the
transformation of the educational system, the reforms in the
management and resource allocation will be carried out in a
limited number of departments (five to eight) and municipalities
(100 to 160); between 500 and 800 schools offering all grades of
basic education will be established under the program, through the
reorganization and consolidation of existing schools.
</P>
<P>
Participation in the program by departments, municipalities,
and schools will be voluntary. The participating departments will
sign agreements with the National Ministry of Education to
undertake the refrom process. The program will finance technical
assistance, as well as incentives, to carry out the reforms.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the program is 76 million dollars. The IDB
loan is for a 25-year term, with a four-year grace period, at the
variable annual interest rate, now 6.84 percent. Local counterpart
funds total 40 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
