<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Population Growth Slows down Because of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe, with a population
of 12.5 million, saw its population growth down to 1.4 percent,
but it would have been 2.4 percent were it not for the AIDS
pandemic.
</P>
<P>
Launching the 1999 State of the World Population Report,
Zimbabwean State Planning Minister Swithun Mombeshora said on
Wednesday that it was disheartening that HIV/AIDS is the
significant culprit for the fall.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, average life expectancy now standing
at 44 years was expected to fall to 41 in the years between 2000
and 2005, 25 years less than what would be expected in the
absence of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is second to Botswana on the world list of countries
worst affected by AIDS. About 1.4 million adults, or 25.8
percent of sexually active adults between 15 and 49 years are
thought to be infected with HIV.
</P>
<P>
Cumulative AIDS cases since 1985 are estimated to be 650,000.
More than 700 people die every week from HIV/AIDS-related disease.
</P>
<P>
Mombeshora said that even though there was a decrease in
population growth, many people were still living in poverty.
</P>
</TEXT>
