<HEADLINE> Angola's Debts to Portugal Hits $679 million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 22 (xinhua) -- Angola is in heavy debt to
Portugal, with the amount of the official debts reaching 679
million U.S. dollars by the end of 1998, official news agency
Angop reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Angola's official debts to the Portuguese government
has increased by four percent, or 24 million dollars, from 655
million dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Angola's official debts in arrears to Portugal, the second
largest creditor to Angola, hit 233 million dollars in 1998,
increasing by 68 percent from 139 million dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Angola owes one billion dollars to Portuguese
private creditors.
</P>
<P>
Among the five portuguese-speaking African countries, Angola is
the biggest debtor to Portugal, followed by Mozambique with 444
million dollars, Guinea Bissau, 77 million, Cape Verde, 31 million
and Sao Tome e Principe 29 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The southwest African country has a total external debts of 13
billion dollars, with Russia as its largest creditor country, to
which Angola owes 7 billion dollars which was spent on arms import
 from the former Soviet Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
