<HEADLINE> Latvia Seeks More Important U.N. Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Latvia Wednesday
voiced its full support to the U.N. reform, and its hope to see
the United Nations play a more important role in the international
community.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Vaira Vike-Freigberga, president of
Latvia, addressed the session at the general debate of the 54th
General Assembly session.
</P>
<P>
"The reform process of the U.N. is underway and my country,
Latvia, fully supports it," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the negative feelings about the U.N. stem from
over-expectation," she said. "One cannot view the U.N. as a
panacea, particularly where decisions on long-lasting regional
problems are concerned or when preventive actions on a regional
level had been long overdue."
</P>
<P>
"Yet, even in those situation a modern U.N. system is expected
to look for earlier and more effective involvement than it has
been the case in Southeast Europe, East Timor and the Middle
East," she said.
</P>
<P>
"It needs to be stressed that the painful refugee crisis of
Kosovo could not possibly be resolved without direct involvement
of the U.N. and its institutions," she said.
</P>
<P>
"But sadly, the maximum potential of the United Nations cannot
always be utilized because of prejudice, lack of political will
or perceived political ambitions," she said.
</P>
<P>
The topical issues of cooperation at regional and global level
and conflict prevention, non-proliferation, arms control and
disarmament, humanitarian, environmental protection, follow-up to
U.N. conferences, poverty eradication and gender equality need to
be addressed on a global scale, she said.
</P>
<P>
"Without a doubt, the United Nations and its institutions
have to play an increasingly important role to this end," she
said.
</P>
<P>
"The mandate of the United Nations is to serve humanity, and
the United Nations should observe the principle of universality,"
she said. "The U.N.'s possibilities in conflict prevention and
preventive diplomacy are by no means exhausted and further
attention should be paid to fostering the observance of these
principles throughout the world."  
</P>
</TEXT>
