<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hamas Raps Jordan Over Arrest of Its Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Militant Palestinian Resistance
Movement (Hamas) Wednesday condemned Jordan over the arrest of two
of the group's leaders, and hoped the issue can be solved through
dialog and mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
Hamas made the condemnation in a statement issued Wednesday in
Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Jordanian police arrested two leaders of
Hamas and denied the entry to the third into the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Khaled Mashaal, Moussa Abu Marzuk and Ibrahim Ghosheh, senior
Hamas members who are based in Amman, was detained upon their
arrival at the Amman airport aboard a United Arab Emirates flight
from Iran.
</P>
<P>
Denouncing the arrests and entry-denial as "unreasonable,"
Hamas held Amman fully responsible for the crackdown and hoped
such an act will not be repeated.
</P>
<P>
After a brief interrogation at the airport, police released
Abu Marzuk who holds a Yemeni passport, but denied his entry into
Jordan and asked him to "leave the country for any destination he
wishes".
</P>
<P>
The other two men, who are Jordanian citizens, faced charges of
engaging in illegal political activities in the kingdom and a
possible one-year prison term if convicted under the Jordanian
law.
</P>
<P>
The arrests are apparently another step by Jordanian
authorities to crack down on the Hamas movement after police shut
down the Hamas office in Amman and arrested 12 of its members on
August 30.
</P>
<P>
Police also issued arrest warrants against Hamas spokesman
Ibrahim Ghosheh, former politburo chief Abu Marzuk, current leader
of the movement`s politburo Khaled Mashaal and Hamas representative
in Jordan Mohammad Nazzal, who were then on a visit to Iran.
</P>
<P>
The whereabout of Mohammad Nazzal is not immediately clear.
</P>
<P>
Hamas is known as a militant Palestinian organization which
opposes the peace process between Israel and the Palestinians and
stands for a "holy war" to liberate all Palestinians territories
to establish an Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is a staunch supporter of the Palestinians but called
for an early resumption of peace talks between Israel and the
Palestinians as well as Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, becoming
the second Arab country after Egypt to strike a peace deal
with the Jewish state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
