<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Official Says Money Laundering Fully Investigated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The alleged illegal
diversion of money from Russia to the United States was being
fully investigated, a senior U.S. justice official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Testifying before the House Banking Committee, Assistant
Attorney General James Robinson said that the investigation has
been and will be "complex and painstaking."
</P>
<P>
"We do not want to become the world's repository of foreign
criminal proceeds," Robinson said, adding that additional tools
were required for law enforcement to combat the problem of money
laundering.
</P>
<P>
Also testifying Wednesday, Bank of New York Chairman and Chief
Executive Thomas Renyi admitted before the committee that there
had been a "lapse" in internal controls at his bank, but he
stressed the bank had not been accused of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
The bank had failed to act quickly enough to question large
flows of funds through accounts held by the relatives of one of
the bank's executives.
</P>
<P>
"Allowing these accounts to remain open and active without
sufficient questioning was a lapse on the part of the bank," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration said it will ensure that the full
story was uncovered behind those transactions and bring any
criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
Robinson was reluctant to discuss specifics of the case because
the investigation by the FBI and federal prosecutors in New York
City was ongoing, stressing the need to protect witnesses.
</P>
<P>
U.S. media reports said late last month that up to 10 billion
U.S. dollars had been illegally channeled to the Bank of New York,
possibly including some of the loans by the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Moscow, Washington and the IMF have indicated that no evidence
was found to prove that IMF loans have been illegally diverted.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, a high-ranking delegation of the Russian
law enforcement agencies visited Washington and had meetings with
the U.S. authorities over the alleged money laundering.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Ministry of the Interior estimated in 1998 that at
least 300 billion U.S. dollars had been looted from Russia. It was
reported that 1 billion to 2 billion U.S. dollars was diverted to
foreign banks from Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
