<HEADLINE> Arafat to Tell Clinton New ideas on Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton will meet Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on Thursday and
hear him about some new ideas on the Middle East peace process,
the White House said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Arafat requested to meet with the president to review some
of his latest ideas on moving the peace process forward," said
Mike Hammer, a spokesman for the White House national Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time for the two leaders to meet since
Arafat signed a new peace agreement with Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak on September 5 and opened the door to talks on a final
settlement.
</P>
<P>
Hammer said he did not know what ideas Arafat would tell
President Clinton. He said the United States sees the peace
process as proceeding on track after the revised peace deal was
signed at Sharm el-Sheikhh in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Israel has released 199 Palestinian prisoners and transferred
a further seven percent of the West Bank to the Palestinian
Authority since the revised peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright met
with Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara in New York on
Wednesday on the fringes of the opening of the U.N. General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Shara said there had been no breakthrough for the resumption
of the peace negotiations on Syria-Israel track. But he said
Syria would continue its contact with the United States seen as
a go-between.  
</P>
