<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Ministers to Meet in Tanzania to Facilitate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) said Wednesday that 14 ministers of
its member states will meet in Dar-es-Salaam next month to pave
way for implementing a free trade protocol.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will address the remaining obstacles to the
free-trade agreement for the region, SADC deputy director Marina
Mayer told South African parliament's trade and industry
committee.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is aimed at producing a free-trade bloc in
southern Africa by 2004 and to accelerate the economic development
of the region.
</P>
<P>
But the member states have not agreed on a timetable for
reducing trade barriers between them and on rules-of-origin
provisions of the trade protocol, which determine what percentage
of a product has to be locally produced in a country before it can
be exported at reduced tariffs, she said, quoted by South African
Press Association.
</P>
<P>
Mayer said the Southern African Customs Union (SACU) was
objecting to the percentage of their products other countries,
such as Mozambique and Zimbabwe, want to exclude from tariff
elimination over a number of years.
</P>
<P>
SACU, comprising Botswana, Lesotho, Namibia, South Africa and
Swaziland, is refusing to allow SADC states to export textiles,
clothing and processed agricultural goods that have a high
foreign-made content at reduced tariffs.
</P>
<P>
Mayer said South Africa was hoping that SADC trade ministers
would show the political will to resolve the deadlock on the
issues when they meet in the Tanzanian capital in the last week of
October.
</P>
<P>
If they do not, she said, the South African parliament would
proceed to ratify proposals on rules of origin and the timetable
for the lowering of tariffs which have already been agreed to by
other SACU states.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is planning to ratify the deal before the end of
November. Five other countries presently are in the process of
ratifying it, which would allow implementation to start in
January.
</P>
<P>
Ten spatial development initiatives, which open trade and
development corridors between countries, are expected to be
created as part of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
However, those planned for Angola and the Democratic Republic
of the Congo were unlikely to proceed because of the wars there,
Mayer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
