<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Excavate 18th Century Shipwreck </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- An 18th century
shipwreck buried deep in the sea believed to be worth over 120
million rand (20 million U.S. dollars) is to be recovered from off
the coast of Cape Agulhas, Network Radio News reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to get under way in February next year.
</P>
<P>
It will be South Africa's first hi-tech deep water
archaeological excavation of a shipwreck ever.
</P>
<P>
The Brederode went down near Cape Agulhas in May 1785 while on
its way home to China. It was carrying a cargo of satin, spices
and tea for the Dutch East India Company.
</P>
<P>
The Brederode is thought to have struck an uncharted reef.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists believe that the hull of the ship is still
intact under the sand.
</P>
<P>
A unique legal agreement between the salvage team, the National
 Monuments Council and the Maritime Museum has been struck for the
wreck's excavation.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the agreement, the exploration team will get the
bulk of the excavated goods, but the museum will get a sample of
everything of cultural or historical importance.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists hope to raise the Brederode's cargo of precious
Chinese porcelain and 80 tons of perfectly-preserved tin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Survey Shows U.S. Economy Still Strong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. is enjoying
"moderate-to-brisk rates of growth" with rising industrial
activity and strong retail sales in most areas of the country,
the Federal Reserve said in a survey Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Fed survey, known as the "beige book," said the strong
economy is contributing to widespread labor shortages.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey said, even with the tight labor market, it
had "few reports of acceleration in nominal wages and salaries
although some districts note a substantial upswing in the cost of
health-care benefits." And, consumer prices remain stable, the
survey reported.
</P>
<P>
The "beige book," compiled from reports from its 12 regional
banks, will be used when Fed policy-makers meet Oct. 5 to review
the central bank's stance on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which was based on information collected before
Sept. 13, reported strong growth and tight labor markets, but it
also said inflation generally remains subdued.
</P>
<P>
It said that "price pressures at the consumer level remain
mostly calm, and numerous districts report significant increases
in some materials prices" including lumber and plywood for housing
construction.
</P>
<P>
The Fed said manufacturing activity had accelerated in almost
every district, with Chicago, Cleveland and St. Louis Fed
districts reporting solid demand for steel and other metal
products, particularly for the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
The Boston, Dallas and Minneapolis districts noted strong
demand for semiconductors and computer components while the San
Francisco district said demand from markets in East Asia, the area
hardest hit by the global currency crisis, was beginning to
rebound.
</P>
<P>
The survey noted that many districts reported strong
back-to-school sales and even stronger demand for new autos.
</P>
<P>
It said the recent drought had worsened crop and livestock
conditions in the East and parts of the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
The Chicago, Cleveland, Richmond and St. Louis districts rated
corn and soybean crops as in poor to fair condition. The San
Francisco district said adverse weather had lowered the quality
and yield of many grain, fruit and vegetable crops.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, Dallas, Kansas City and Minneapolis reported
favorable agriculture conditions with corn and soybean crops rated
as good to excellent with above average yields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
