<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Liberalize Telecom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican government on
Wednesday submitted a bill to the parliament on liberalization of
the country's telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the bill, Deputy Transport and communications
Minister Antonio Fernandes said that the government also intends
to privatize the national telecommunications company, TDM , adding
that the state will maintain a significant shareholding.
</P>
<P>
He argued that bringing private capital into TDM was the only
way to provide it with the muscle to ensure its survival in a
competitive situation.
</P>
<P>
He said that the viability study for TDM's privatization
should start in January.
</P>
<P>
The bill envisages opening the cellular phone market to
competition at once. This means that there could be a competitor
to the current operator, M-Cel (a joint venture between TDM and
Deutsche Telecom of Germany), by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
But opening the fixed telephone network to competition will
not take place until five years after TDM's privatization.
</P>
<P>
Fernandes argued that the introduction of competition would
push down the price of phone calls.
</P>
<P>
The pailament will debate over the bill on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
