<HEADLINE> Second UK Auction Sends Gold Price Surging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The prices of gold leapt
sharply in early European trading Wednesday after a
stronger-than-expected response to the Bank of England's second
auction of its reserves.
</P>
<P>
The sale, in which the Bank received 255.75 U.S. dollars an
ounce for its 25 tonnes, sparked a sharp swing in sentiment
towards the depressed metal, prompting speculators to cover short
positions.
</P>
<P>
Having gained close to 5 U.S. dollars an ounce on Tuesday after
the results came through, gold reached higher still in early
business Wednesday, easily breaking through the 261.20 U.S.
dollars achieved at the first auction and touching a bid high of
263.90 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The strong response did not protect the Bank against further
attacks from the gold industry, led by the World Gold Council,
which repeated its heavy criticism of the move.
</P>
<P>
The Bank does not disclose the prices tendered for the gold or
the names of the bidders. However, Gold Fields, the South African
gold mining giant, confessed to having bought 12.5 percent of the
bullion auctioned Tuesday in the belief that "it was cheap".
</P>
<P>
The first British auction, which took place against a
background of other central bank sales over recent months and the
threat of sales from the International Monetary Fund, had dragged
gold to multiple 20-year lows that bottomed at 251.70 U.S. dollars
on August 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
