<HEADLINE> Germany Says Kosovo Shouldn't Be Precedent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Germany said Wednesday
NATO's armed intervention in Kosovo must not set a precedent for
weakening the U.N.'s role in dealing with humanitarian crises.
</P>
<P>
The move should not be a precedent to weaken the U.N. Security
Council's "monopoly" on authorizing the use of international
force, Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer told the 54th Session of
the U.N. General Assembly on the third day of its general debate.
</P>
<P>
"Nor must it become a license to use external force under the
pretext of humanitarian assistance," he said, noting that this
"would open the door to the arbitrary use of power and anarchy,
and throw the world back to the 19th century."
</P>
<P>
The only solution to the issue is to further develop the
existing U.N. system "to intervene in good time in cases of very
grave human rights violations," but not until all peaceful means
of settling conflicts have been exhausted and "within a strictly
limited legal and controlled framework."
</P>
<P>
NATO waged a 78-day air campaign against Yugoslavia on the
pretext of "defending" Kosovo ethnic Albanians from Serbs.
</P>
<P>
The massive military action since March 24 against the
sovereign state of Yugoslavia bypassed the Security Council and
did not get prior consent of the country.
</P>
<P>
It caused a great humanitarian catastrophe by perishing
Yugoslavia's infrastructure and leaving tens of thousands of
people including women and children displaced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
