<HEADLINE> Italians Enjoys Car-Free Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Italian streets were
significantly emptier of traffic Wednesday after a European-wide
initiative aimed at encouraging people to get about town without
their cars.
</P>
<P>
"Italians have proved that they can live without their cars,"
said Environment Minister Edo Ronchi, after many in the 92 Italian
participating cities heeded calls to leave their cars at home and
use public transport instead in an effort to reduce traffic and
pollution.
</P>
<P>
"We have consistently registered a lower volume of traffic in
all cities, even in areas where cars weren't banned from city
centers," said Ronchi, who has championed the cause of
traffic-free city-centers in Italy.
</P>
<P>
In Rome, the Cities Without Cars initiative sponsored by the
European Union was a "resounding" success, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Traffic was also significantly reduced in the northern Italian
towns of Trento, Bolzano and Turin where public transport was free
for the day, according to early estimates.
</P>
<P>
However, Milan, Italy's biggest city, disassociated itself from
the car-free day and Mayor Gabriele Albertini said it was a
"useless" stunt which could not take place in his city while
fashion shows were underway.
</P>
<P>
In the central city of Florence, the central Piazza del Duomo
was closed to traffic for four hours Wednesday morning; in another
central city of Bologna traffic rules were as normal.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey by the Databank polling agency for the
environment ministry, some 84 percent of Italians say they favor
keeping cars out of city centers.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that on a normal working Wednesday 63
percent of Italians take their cars to work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
