<HEADLINE> U.S. New Jobless Claims Fall to Lowest Level in 25 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The number of new claims
for jobless benefits in U.S. dropped last week to the lowest level
in 25 years, the Labor Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Department reported that 272,000 people filed new claims
for unemployment benefits for the week ending Sept. 18, down by
17,000 from the previous week. That was the lowest level since
Jan. 5, 1974, when claims were at 269,000.
</P>
<P>
According to government officials, part of the sharp drop could
have been because some unemployed who were affected by Hurricane
Floyd were unable to get to claims offices. But the officials had
no specific data on the storm's effects.
</P>
<P>
The four-week average for claims also was down last week, to
285,750. That was the lowest level since April 21 when claims were
at 284,500.
</P>
<P>
Last week's decrease in new claims was unexpected. Many
economists had been forecasting that a rise to 290,000. It was the
ninth week in a row that claims were below 300,000.
</P>
<P>
The Department also said that for the week ending Sept. 11, 42
states and territories reported decreases in new jobless claim
applications, while 10 reported increases. The state data lag a
week behind the national figures.
</P>
<P>
The state with the biggest decrease was California, down
4,359, while the state with the biggest increase was North
Carolina, up 902. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
