<P>
Participants will include delegates from 20 African countries,
as well as experts and representatives from research institutions,
African subregional economic organizations, such as the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS), the Southern African
Development Community (SADC), the Arab Magrheb Union, and United
Nations specialized agencies.
</P>
<P>
Delegates will aim to determine the functioning and operational
elements for the Arms Register and Database in Africa, establish
the nature and type of data, sources and users, analyze
shortcomings in compiling statistics and information on light
weapons and identify solutions, and determine the use of an Arms
Register and Database as a mechanism for fostering transparency --
a crucial requirement in building trust, confidence, security and
durable peace in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Accra Workshop is organized by the United Nations Regional
Center for Peace and Disarmament (PCASED) in collaboration with
the Ghanaian Government.
</P>
<P>
The workshop will convene within the framework of the
activities of th Program for Coordination and Assistance for
Security and Development, the technical and secretariat mechanism
established by the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) to
implement the ECOWAS Moratorium, launched on October 31 for a
renewable period of three years.
</P>
<P>
The decision to hold the workshop was taken during a March
1988 meeting in Bamko, Mali, by ECOWAS foreign ministers, during
which they adopted the Plan of Action of PCASED. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
