<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More than 2,100 Killed in Powerful Quake in Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The death toll in the
disastrous earthquake which struck Taiwan on September 21 had
risen to 2,103 by 5 p.m. this evening, with 7,821 injured, 1,641
feared trapped among the collapsed buildings and 210 missing,
media reports monitored here said.
</P>
<P>
An aftershock measuring 5.2 on the Richter scale hit northwest
Hualien at 8:46 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
By 11 a.m., a total of 3,975 aftershocks had been reported
since the tremor struck Tuesday, seismologists said. They said the
aftershocks are becoming fewer as time goes by, but might not stop
completely for two or six months.
</P>
<P>
According to data from the mainland's earthquake monitoring
networks, Tuesday's quake measured 7.6 on the Richter scale, with
its epicenter in southwest Hualien, 145 kilometers (90 miles) from
Taipei.
</P>
<P>
So far, a total of 6,005 houses have toppled, and another 1,569
houses are uninhabitable. Victims are in great need of tents,
drinking water, and other relief goods, local sources said.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the Taiwan authorities show that traffic on the
main roads in central Taiwan has been completely disrupted, and
596 roads have been closed and will not re-open until September 28.
Repair work of some bridges may require up to two months.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the quake has loosened rocks in the mountainous area,
leaving the region more vulnerable to mud-rock flow, local sources
warned.
</P>
<P>
Power shortages brought on by the quake have also led to the
suspension of numerous industries in Taiwan, which has incurred
severe economic losses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
