<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Envoy: Sino-Russian Ties Face Bright Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Ambassador to Russia
Wu Tao said here Thursday that Sino-Russian ties face a bright
future as the two countries march toward the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference on the eve of the 50th anniversary of the
founding of the People's Republic of China and the establishment
of diplomatic ties between China and Russia, Wu said bilateral
relations have matured.
</P>
<P>
The current Sino-Russian strategic partnership of cooperation
oriented toward the 21st century, featuring non-confrontation, non-
alignment and not targeting a third country, confirms the
fundamental interests of both countries, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
He said the two countries are preparing for the autumn visit to
Beijing by Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who will hold the
second informal summit with his Chinese counterpart, Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
The exact date of the visit is being arranged through
diplomatic channels, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging that bilateral economic ties lag behind political
cooperation, Wu said the two sides should work together to
increase their trade in more high-tech and high-value-added
products, to improve the servicing sector of trade and to lower
China's mounting trade deficit with Russia, which has accumulated
to 15 billion U.S. dollars since 1992.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral cooperation in the military-technical field, the
ambassador said cooperation has been conducted at an appropriate
level and that China only purchases limited amounts of military
hardware from Russia for defensive purposes.
</P>
<P>
Wu also dismissed some Russian media reports that said illegal
Chinese immigrants are swarming into Russia, and the Chinese
government encourages illegal immigration to Russia.
</P>
<P>
He said illegal immigrants only account for a very small
percentage of Chinese nationals here and that their action is
motivated by themselves rather than encouraged by China's
government policy.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said it is a good thing for the two countries to
have more personnel exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Chinese border control authorities, Wu said the number
of Russians traveling to China in 1998 and the first half of this
year was about 1 million, which surpassed the number of Chinese
nationals traveling to Russia, about 700,000.
</P>
<P>
"We should base our judgments on facts rather than propaganda."
Wu said, stressing that the Chinese government firmly opposes any
form of illegal immigration to any country because "illegal
immigration not only taints China's image but also adversely
affects China's exchanges with other countries." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
