<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Envoy Hopes for Peace in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Addor Neto, out-going
Brazilian ambassador to Angola, has expressed his hope for the
rapid implementation of peace in the war-torn southern African
country without the existence of one more parallel nation.
</P>
<P>
The civil conflict should be ended as soon as possible "on
condition that there doesn't exist a parallel state in Angola,"
the official news agency Angop Thursday quoted the ambassador as
saying.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the Public Television of Angola, the Brazilian
envoy also urged Angola to keep its air space under control, hence
the government can better detect the clandestine planes carrying
military supplies to the rebels of the National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
After the Angolan civil war renewed in late 1998, the Angolan
government found that Jonas Savimbi had reinforced his UNITA rebel
force during the period of negotiation.
</P>
<P>
At this moment, the troops of the Jose Eduardo dos Santos'
government encounter many difficulties in their battle against the
rebels, which hindered the government from going further in the
rural areas under the control of Savimbi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
