<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO: Basic Health-care Services Needed in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- It is a matter of utmost
urgency to restart basic health-care services in East Timor now
while the world is responding to the plight of the people by
sending medicines and other supplies, World Health Organization (
WHO) Director-General Gro Harlem Brundtland said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Don't put the cart before the horse," Brundtland warned. "For
weeks now, over 800,000 people -- who already had health standards
lower than the rest of Indonesia -- have been deprived of basic
medical care."
</P>
<P>
She called on the United Nations humanitarian coordinator to
help get basic medical care to the people in need, since many
organizations and the personnel are ready and willing to provide
it.
</P>
<P>
She said that nurses, midwives and doctors are urgently needed
to deal with two classes of problems: maternal and child health,
and infectious disease control.
</P>
<P>
"We could have boxes and boxes of supplies on hand, but if
there's no trained medical staff, mothers could die in childbirth,
" the WHO head said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
