<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Biennial World Cup May Cause Economic Damage to European Soccer: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The introduction of a biennial
World Cup system could cause economic damage to the European
soccer and reduce its income by 1 billion U.S. dollars over eight
years, said a report commissioned by the UEFA.
</P>
<P>
"Under the current structure of world football, European
football is unlikely to gain from the introduction of a biennial
World Cup and European championship tournaments," the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, a reduction in the growth rate of top
level competitions of just five percentage points a year could
reduce European soccer's income by over 1 billion U.S. dollars
over an eight year cycle.
</P>
<P>
The report explained, "The overall increase in the supply of
top level football could also affect the value of major club and
TV sponsorship, causing an indirect negative impact."
</P>
<P>
The report also pointed the possible clashes in sports calendar
with the Grand Slam tennis tournaments and the Formula One Grand
Prix circuit.
</P>
<P>
The FIFA President Sepp Blatter was keen on launching the
biennial World Cup system but met opposition from the UEFA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
