<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Moves to Avert Y2K Problem in Aviation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Manila International
Airport Authority (MIAA) Thursday hosted a Y2K contingency
conference to address the Y2K problem in the Philippines' aviation
sector.
</P>
<P>
The one-day meeting was conducted by International Air Travel
Association (IATA) representatives -- Kok Ming Cheang of Singapore
and Chris Drabble from the United Kingdom, Philippine News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Present at meeting were Philippine representatives from the
MIAA, Cebu International Airport Authority, Clark International
Airport and Subic International Airport and officials of different
local and international airlines.
</P>
<P>
Participants discussed such issues as how to ensure the
Philippine airports and airline business keep normal operation in
the face of Y2K-related problems.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K problem or millennium bug stems from an oversight by
computer software developers designating only by last two digits
so that early computers will be unable to correctly recognize year
2000 from 1900.
</P>
<P>
To minimize the adverse effects of Y2K problems, the
participants adopted the Joint-Airport-Airline Year 2000 Liaison
Program, which encourages cooperation and communication among
aviation industry players in developing their respective
contingency plans.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, airport authorities should share information
with their partners in the industry and draw business plans that
can be achieved to sustain public and business confidence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
