<HEADLINE> Things Ready for China's National Minorities Games, Says Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Everything is ready for the
Sixth National Games for Traditional Sports of Minority
Nationalities opening here Friday, a leading official of the event
's organizing committee announced here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Although the opening ceremony is to begin 8:00 PM Friday in the
Workers' Stadium in the Chinese capital, the winner of the first
gold medal, however, will be declared around 9:00 AM, in the horse
racing competitions, Wan Siquan, vice-chairman of the organizing
committee, said at a press conference on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony coincides with the traditional Chinese Mid-
autumn Festival featuring a feat of "moon cakes".
</P>
<P>
All the 34 participating delegations have arrived in Beijing,
including the one from Chinese Taipei, where an earthquake on
Tuesday was reported to have killed more than 2,100 persons. Only
58 of the 120 delegates reached Beijing via Hong Kong on Wednesday,
due to infrastructure destruction in Taiwan caused by the tumbler,
according to a leading official of the delegation.
</P>
<P>
Athletes from Chinese Taipei will compete in the dragon boat
racing event here.
</P>
<P>
By noon of Thursday, some 3,000 out of a total Games entry of 3,
200 had checked-in in various Beijing hotels assigned for the
event, with more still on the way.
</P>
<P>
Beijing and Lhasa, capital city of southwestern China's Tibet
Autonomous Region, were chosen as venues for the quadrennial Games
inaugurated in 1953. Competitions including three medal sports
for the Lhasa venue were held August 18-23 this year.
</P>
<P>
The week-long competitions in Beijing feature 10 medal sports
including archery, wrestling, martial arts and horse racing as
well as over 110 demonstration events, among the most favored
pastimes of the country's minority nationalities.
</P>
<P>
All the participants of the Beijing Games have been invited to
attend the grand parade and other celebrations for the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China on
October 1, one day after the Games close. 
</P>
</TEXT>
