<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB, Italy Agree to Establish Grant Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) and the Italian government agreed Thursday to establish an
Italy-aided fund to finance technical assistance activities in the
bank's developing member countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, Italy will make an initial
contribution of 5 billion Italian lire (3 million U.S. dollars) to
finance activities such as project preparation, advisory services
and project implementation, the ADB said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
The fund, which is called the Italian Cooperation Fund for
Consulting Services, will be administered by the ADB. Italy and
the ADB will have to agree on the projects to be financed under
the fund.
</P>
<P>
Technical assistance plays an important role in the bank's
operations by helping developing member countries identify,
design, implement and operate development projects.
</P>
<P>
Such assistance not only strengthens the member countries'
ability to formulate development strategies, policies, programs
and plans but also promotes technology transfer and regional
cooperation, the ADB said.
</P>
<P>
As of December 31, 1998, the ADB had provided nearly 4,000
technical assistance grants worth 1.36 billion dollars to its
developing member countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
