<HEADLINE> France Calls for U.N. Security Council Declaration on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- France has called on the United
Nations Security Council to make a declaration this week regarding
a solution to the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said earlier this week
in New York that France hopes the five permanent members of the
Security Council will make greater efforts to resolve humanitarian
problems caused by the embargo on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
France suggested at the beginning of this year that the U.N.
Council review its policy "on a new basis" toward Iraq, including
an efficient new control system to make sure that Iraq does not
arm itself again with weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Such a monitoring system should prevent Iraq from using its
income from oil exports to obtain such arms, according to the
French proposal.
</P>
<P>
"From such a system and controls, the U.N. could lift the
embargo, which is a primitive approach and very cruel to Iraqi
society," said Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
He said the international community should "absolutely give an
answer" to the humanitarian disaster in Iraq, but at the same time
"seriously take into account regional security."
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said the United States and Britain are not
"completely against" the French proposal.
</P>
<P>
France has been criticizing the U.S.-British air raids against
Iraq and wants the U.N. to lift its economic sanctions against
Iraq on the condition that Baghdad stick to its commitment on
disarmament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
