<HEADLINE> Cyprus Peace Talks to Start in Mid-October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan is expected to call the two sides in Cyprus to
three-week-long peace talks in mid-October, in West Point of the
U.S., according to Cyprus News Agency (CNA) Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The invitations will be extended at the end of this month
after a meeting between U.S. President Bill Clinton and Turkish
Premier Bulent Ecevit on September 28, in Washington, a CNA report
from New York said.
</P>
<P>
The news agency quoted reliable sources as saying that Annan is
expected to preside over the talks, with American and British
representatives in the wings. U.S. officials have prepared
scenarios that they will present at the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the talks will break after three weeks so that
the Cyprus president can attend November's Commonwealth summit in
South Africa and the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
European summit in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, the U.S. president is scheduled to visit
Ankara and Athens, where he will act depending on the outcome of
the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
All meetings relating to the Cyprus peace talks are expected to
conclude before December's European Union (EU) summit in Helsinki,
as Turkey's EU prospect is one issue that is attractive for both
Ankara and Turkish Cypriot side.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking with union Athens.
</P>
<P>
The seven most industrialized nations plus Russia (G-8), in
their June summit in Cologne, Germany, asked the U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan to invite leaders of the two communities to
unconditional negotiations in the fall of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriot side has made it clear that it wants peace
talks to take place, but will not accept the preconditions set out
by Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Denktash insists that he would not enter into negotiations
unless his breakaway state in northern Cyprus, backed by Turkey,
be internationally recognized and talk with Nicosia on
state-to-state basis.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Kofi Annan is concerned with the possibility
of the talks failing, but the U.S. and British foreign ministers
have asked him to go ahead and extend the invitations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
