<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Bombs Grozny Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Defense Ministry
on Thursday confirmed that federal fighter jets fired a missile on
the Grozny airport early in the day and destroyed an AN-2 plane "
which militants used for the delivery of arms and munitions across
Chechen territory.
</P>
<P>
"The air force will continue attacking targets which militants
use," Interfax news agency reported the ministry press service as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The headquarters of the federal force in the North Caucasus
said earlier that the air strikes were conducted over arms depots
and at an airport radar station militants were using.
</P>
<P>
"The radar tracked Russian flights over Chechnya and supplied
information to the terrorists," a headquarters source told
Interfax.
</P>
<P>
In addition, attacks were also made at a fuel storage and
lubricants facility, arms and munitions depots, a power sub-
station and an oil refinery, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
In Grozny, capital city of the breakaway republic, local
authorities said an airport technician was killed in the air raid,
which took place shortly after midday Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They said the AN-2 plane, the only one available in Chechnya,
was used for agricultural purposes and from which parachutists
jumped during festive occasions.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Defense Ministry is also considering the
possibility of using heavy bombers capable of carrying more
powerful weapons to deliver air strikes against rebel bases in
Chechnya, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Tactical bombers such as Tu-22m2 and Tu-22m3 may be deployed to
deliver more powerful air strikes, Interfax quoted ministry
sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Until recently, air strikes on rebel bases were carried out by
Su-24 front-line bombers and Su-25 attack planes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
