<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Israel Denies Palestinians Family Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Both Israel and the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) currently have more than
13,000 Palestinian requests pending for family unifications in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed here Thursday by the Center for the Defense
of the Individuals in its report, which presents the historical
background, the social and legal aspects of the separation of
Palestinian families in the occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
The report contains research on 1,573 complaints handled by
the center from 1961 to 1996 and data on 100 separated Palestinian
families from Bani Naim Village near the West Bank city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Israel has never recognized the right of Palestinian
residents of the occupied territories to family unification, nor
to have residents' spouses and children receive the legal status
of resident, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Over the years, it said, the Israeli authorities have approved
family unification infrequently and according to undisclosed
criteria.
</P>
<P>
The situation did not change following the signing of the Oslo
Accord, because Israel continues to decide which Palestinian
families are allowed to live together in the territories and
which must remain separated, it added.
</P>
<P>
"Requests filed now will take almost a decade to be approved.
Consequently, a Palestinian who marries a non-resident today will
only be able to live with his or her spouse in the West Bank 10
years from now, or never," the reported pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Marriage between residents of the occupied territories and
non-resident Palestinians is widespread, tens of thousands of
Palestinians have been compelled to live apart from their
spouses, leaving their children to live for long periods without
one of their parents, it said.
</P>
<P>
In the vast majority of cases, the only way residents of the
occupied territories married to non-residents may live together
lawfully is to leave the territories, thereby abandoning their
houses, parents and homeland, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
