<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
MANAMA -- The "Arab Jewels Exhibition 99" will be held in
Bahrain on November 9-13 with the participation of leading
jewelers in the world.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Thursday that some 200 exhibitors from 20
countries will take part in the event.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will restrict the evening hours to investors and
businessmen who wish to make deals, and will set November 11 to
women visitors only.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq has exported on September 11-17 13.4 million
barrels of crude oil, valued at 281 million U.S. dollars, under
the sixth phase of oil-for-food program with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement released by the U.N. Iraq Program
Office, Iraq has exported a total of 234.5 million barrels of
crude oil with a total value of 4.215 billion dollars ever since
the commencement of the sixth phase on June 1.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's oil production dropped by 1.57 percent to
19.94 million tons in the first half this year from the same
period last year, the country's Middle East News Agency reported
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A report issued by the Egyptian General Petroleum Corporation
said the production of gas and gas derivatives rose by 11.85
percent in the first six months in 1999 to 7.51 million tons from
the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The crude oil refined in domestic refineries totaled 14.39
million tons in the first six months in 1999, down 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Domestic consumption of oil products and natural gas during the
first half of 1999 stood at 17.82 million tons, up 4.2 percent
from the corresponding period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Central Bank of Egypt has reported a rise of about
4.5 billion Egyptian pounds (1.32 billion dollars ) in the
expenditures of state budget for the 1998-99 fiscal year ending on
June 30.
</P>
<P>
A report issued by the bank attributed the increase of the
spendings totaling 75.3 billion pounds (22.15 billion dollars) to
a rise by 2-4 percent of the interests of Egypt's debts.
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- The week-long Algerian International Book Fair
opened here Thursday with the participation of some 100 foreign
publishing houses, 10 Algerian publishers and 12 Algerian
distributors.
</P>
<P>
The fair will be coupled with the holding of seminars on Arab
and African literature.
</P>
<P>
An exhibition of Algerian plastic arts will take place on the
sideline of the book fair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
