<HEADLINE> Academy of Sciences Lays Foundation for New Library </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Academy of
Sciences (CAS) laid the foundation for its new library and
archives museum in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
The current CAS library, which was built in April of 1950, has
already become a state-level science and technology library and a
center of scientific archives. It now has a collection of more
than six million books.
</P>
<P>
To increase the library's floor space and provide an upgraded
environment for readers, the CAS has decided to build a new
library just two blocks away from the old one in Zhongguancun,
northwest Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The new library will cover an area of 18,000 sq. meters. The
top two floors of the nine-story library will be used to hold the
museum archives.
</P>
<P>
When it is completed in 2001, the library will be able to serve
1,200 readers a day and provide round-the-clock service for more
than 5,000 Internet users.
</P>
<P>
The archives museum is expected to collect 350,000 sets of
records in various categories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
