<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Does not Recognize Palestinians' Rights to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Israel has never recognized
the rights of Palestinian residents in the occupied territories to
family unification, said a report by the Center for the Defense of
the Individuals Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report said both Israel and the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) have currently received more than 13,000 requests
by Palestinians pending for family unifications in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The center, which is charged with collecting historical
background, social and legal aspects of the separation of
Palestinian families in the occupied territories, conducted
research on 1,573 complaints received from 1961 to 1996 and data
on 100 separated Palestinian families from Bani Naim Village near
the West Bank city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
"Requests filed now will take almost a decade to be
approved. Consequently, a Palestinian who marries a non-resident
today will only be able to live with his or her spouse in the West
Bank ten years from now, or never," said the report.
</P>
<P>
Marriage between residents of the occupied territories and
non-resident Palestinians is common. However, tens of thousands of
Palestinians have to live apart from their spouses, leaving their
children to live for long periods without one of their parents, it
said.
</P>
<P>
In the vast majority of cases, the only way residents of the
occupied territories married to non-residents may live together
lawfully is to leave the territories, thereby abandoning their
houses, parents and homeland, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
