<HEADLINE> Britain to Intensify Efforts for Cyprus Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook has assured that his country will intensify efforts to
secure success in the negotiations on Cyprus, the Cyprus News
Agency (CNA) reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cook gave the assurance to his Cyprus counterpart Ioannis
Kasoulides during a meeting in New York Wednesday on the sidelines
of the 54th session of the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers discussed efforts to convene talks on
settling the Cyprus issue in accordance with U.N. Security Council
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the international community has been trying to
bring the two sides to the negotiation table for reunification
through a bicommunal settlement. But no tangible progress has
been made.
</P>
<P>
The seven most industrialized nations plus Russia (G-8), in
their Cologne summit in June, asked U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan to invite the leaders of the two sides to unconditional
negotiations in the autumn of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriot side has said it expects to be invited to
the talks in the second half of October.
</P>
<P>
However, the prospect of holding such talks remains gloomy as
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash insists that he will not
attend the talks unless his breakaway state in northern Cyprus,
backed by Turkey, be recognized by the international community and
talks with Nicosia based on an equal basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
