<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Ancient Chinese Tradition Big Hit at National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A moving story date back as
early as some 2,300 years ago in ancient China later became a
popular sporting event in many Chinese provinces.
</P>
<P>
And it is now expected to become a big hit at China's Sixth
National Games for Traditional Sports of Minority Nationalities
opening here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Dragon boat races, which feature a heated contest among teams
each consisting as many as more than 20 rowers. Members of a team
aboard a slim wooden boat decorated into the shape of a dragon row
in surprisingly neat and rhythmic motion to push their boat
forward as fast as possible. The fastest boat in the race is
declared the winner.
</P>
<P>
Dragon boat racing can inaugurate to ancient China's Warring
States period (475-221 B.C.). Qu Yuan, a patriotic and popular
poet of the Chu State at the time, committed suicide in 278 B.C.
by drowning himself in River Miluo located in what is now southern
China's Hunan Province, after his mini-state was destroyed by
invaders. Many local people set off aboard boats, trying in vain
to receive his body.
</P>
<P>
Commemorative dragon boat races were thus been annually held
along the river at the date of Qu's death and it became a popular
sporting event later in many Chinese provinces.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to enthusiastic introduction by overseas Chinese, dragon
boat racing has become increasingly popular in many other
countries and regions and races are annually held worldwide.
Finland, for example, has held annual dragon boat races since 1990,
with up to 225 teams participating in last year's event.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese team with rowers from south China's Guangdong
Province won the world dragon boat racing championship in Hong
Kong, China, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Dragon boat racing has been a competition event of China's
National Games of Traditional Sports of Minority Nationalities
since the fourth version in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The week-long competition of this year's Games here will see
actions by some 500 athletes in 19 racing teams from 11 Chinese
provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions, which is the
largest field for the event since 1991.
</P>
<P>
And racing teams from Beijing, Yunnan Province, Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region and Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region will make
their debut in Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Police Probe Another Complaint About Netanyahu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Israeli police are
investigating a complaint against former prime minister Benjamin
Netanyahu concerning "breach of trust and the illegal transfer of
state funds to foreign elements."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu was allegedly involved in transferring one million
shekels (298,000 U.S. dollars) from an association that organized
Israel's jubilee celebrations in 1998 to the organizers of the
jubilee events in the United States.
</P>
<P>
A Justice Ministry spokesman was quoted by the local daily
Haaretz as saying Thursday that the matter is being investigated
by the police.
</P>
<P>
The confirmation was given in reaction to a claim by Ami Carmon
that Attorney General Elyakam Rubinstein has ordered the police
not to look into the complaint, which was submitted more than nine
months ago.
</P>
<P>
Carmon noted that in June 1996, shortly after being elected
prime minister, Netanyahu named two close American friends, Merv
Adelson and Marvin Josephson, to be responsible for the jubilee
celebrations outside Israel.
</P>
<P>
The focal point of the complaint was that the Israeli
association in charge of the celebrations had not received the
bills to cover the American groups' expenses, but the transfer was
made to the U.S. at the directive of the prime minister's office.
</P>
<P>
Carmon, who is close to Prime Minister Ehud Barak and bears
the title "head of the One Israel reaction team," stated that
Barak has no connection with the matter.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and his wife Sara are currently under police
investigation on suspicions of taking bribes and misusing of state
funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
