<HEADLINE> Iraq Claims UN Committee Block Over 300 Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Trade Ministry has
accused the U.N. Sanctions Committee of blocking 328 contracts
worth 438 million U.S. dollars signed under the fifth and sixth
phases of the oil-for-food program, Iraqi News Agency reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed spokesman for the ministry accused the U.S. and
British governments of practicing a genocide policy against the
Iraqi people through a deliberate impediment in the approval of
Iraqi contracts by their representatives at the Sanctions
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that those 328 contracts included 116 for
oil sector, 90 for electricity sector, 48 for health sector, 20
for education sector and 54 for other sectors.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the U.S. and Britain intend to kill more
innocent Iraqi people. He called upon the international community
to put pressure on the U.S. and British governments to lift the
embargo imposed on Iraq nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food deal, now in its sixth phase which
expires in November, Iraq is allowed to sell limited amount of
oil in every six months to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian supplies for its 24 million people.
</P>
<P>
Since the fourth phase of the deal, the ceiling of the amount
of oil Iraq is allowed to sell has been raised to 5.2 billion
dollars from 2 billion dollars for the first three phases.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has long accused the U.S. and British envoys in the
Sanctions Committee of hampering the endorsement of its
contracts, arguing that the oil-for-food deal has failed to
alleviate the suffering of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF), mortality rates among Iraqi children have doubled since
the imposition of the U.N. sanctions in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's Health Ministry announced on Sunday that nearly 8,000
Iraqi children aged under five died in last August of different
curable diseases and malnutrition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
