<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Ho Chi Minh City Expects Sharp Export Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Exports of Ho Chi Minh City in
the first nine months of this year are expected to reach 3.3
billion U.S. dollars, up 23 percent from the same period last
year, Vietnam's business newspaper The Saigon Times Daily reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the city statistical bureau, exports in this month
alone are expected to reach 463 million dollars, up 10.9 percent
from last month.
</P>
<P>
Fisheries exports are expected to be 153 million dollars in the
first nine months, up 13.6 percent from the same period last year.
Exports of forestry products are estimated at 31 million dollars,
up 28.3 percent from the year-ago level.
</P>
<P>
However, the high export growth is mainly due to the increase
in the volume and value of crude oil exports, which are expected
to push the export of industrial products up 37.7 percent over the
year-ago level. This sector will account for 81.3 percent of the
city's total export value in the first nine months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, exports of agro-products will fall 23.5 percent from
the year-ago level due to falling shipments of most items
belonging to this group. For instance, rice exports will fall 18.5
percent, coffee down 37.2 percent, and cashew nuts down 45.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam's largest economic hub, is expected
to import 2.45 billion dollars worth of products in the first nine
months of this year, down 4.8 percent from the year-ago level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
