<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Chinese Cuisine Recipes Found in Han Dynasty Tomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Several ancient Chinese
cuisine recipes recorded on bamboo slips which may date back more
than 2,000 years have been unearthed from a Han Dynasty tomb in
central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists believe that this find in Yuanling County in
western Hunan is the oldest food recipes ever found in the country.
The recipes are written in ink on 20 pieces of bamboo slips and
detail cooking procedures for rice and other dishes, as well as
ways to mix beverages and make smoked meats.
</P>
<P>
Hu Pingsheng, a member of the Chinese Relic Research Institute,
said that Chinese archeologists have collected the names of many
ancient dishes from historical records of the Qin and Han
dynasties (221 B.C.-A.D. 24). The cooking methods, however, have
never been found before.
</P>
<P>
He said his excavation team found that the recipes written on
20 bamboo slips were divided into two categories to separate the
cooking of rice from other dishes, and the largest serial number
of the recipes is 46.
</P>
<P>
According to the recipes, there are nine kinds of rice and
seven ways to cook them. Meat dishes include pork, beef, rabbit,
deer and fish.
</P>
<P>
"The recipes were recorded in such a detail that we can
understand how people in ancient times butchered animals, cleaned
the viscera, and cooked and presented the dishes," Hu said.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists here believed that they have found only a small
fragment of a complete recipe book, but it is enough to see how
luxurious the imperial life was at that time.
</P>
<P>
The occupant of the tomb was identified as Wu Yang, a high
ranking official guarding Yuanling Prefecture during the Western
Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-A.D.24). He died and was buried in 162 B.C.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
