<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Further Open Insurance Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- China will further open its
market to foreign insurance companies, Wu Dingfu, vice-chairman of
the China Insurance Regulatory Commission (CIRC) said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a symposium on insurance regulation, the official
said that as China's insurance legislation and regulatory capacity
improves gradually, the country would allow more foreign insurers
into its market and open more Chinese regions to them.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, when China opened its insurance market on an
experimental basis, nine insurance firms from eight countries have
opened 12 organizations in Shanghai and Guangzhou, the only two
Chinese cities now open to foreign insurers.
</P>
<P>
In April 1998, the CIRC gave its go-ahead to another four
foreign insurers to start business in China.
</P>
<P>
Wu said, "The experiment of opening the Chinese insurance
market was successful and has had a good effect."
</P>
<P>
As part of the CIRC's efforts to improve its supervision over
the market at the grassroots level, Wu said, its regulators will
have offices in all the regions of China by the end of next year,
and the first ones will be operational this year.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that the CIRC is taking a positive attitude
toward the establishment of insurers' associations, which would
promote self-regulation among their members.
</P>
<P>
At present, more than 20 Chinese regions have established
insurers' associations. Wu said a national insurers' association
is also being prepared. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
