<HEADLINE> World Bank to Fund Kenya's AIDS Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank may soon
approve a 2.3- billion-shillings grant (around 30 million U.S.
dollars) to support Kenya's HIV/AIDS campaign, Public Health
Minister Sam Ongeri said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks upon his arrival in the capital
Nairobi from Washington, D.C., where he attended an AIDS symposium
and had discussions with World Bank officials over the AIDS
problems in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper Thursday quoted Ongeri as
saying a team from the World Bank is already in the country on a
fact-finding mission of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the team in Kenya would approve the grant package
in assisting his ministry in fighting AIDS in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that at the symposium, he presented the
country's 1997 sessional paper on AIDS and tabled the strategy
plan of his ministry for 1999 to 2004.
</P>
<P>
Ongeri also disclosed that Sandra Thuman, Director of the U.S.
National AIDS Program and President Clinton's Advisor on AIDS
worldwide, had asked the Congress to provide one billion dollars
to Africa for its HIV/AIDS campaign for a five-year period.
</P>
<P>
According to Ongeri, the number of people living with HIV/AIDS
in Kenya was increasing quickly from 3.8 percent in 1980 to 13.9
percent in 1998. The current population of Kenya is estimated at
30 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
