<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,400-Year-Old White-Marble Coffin Found in Shanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
found a 1,400-year-old outer coffin made of white marble in this
capital of north China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The coffin was unearthed from a tomb dating back to the Sui
Dynasty (586-618), according to experts.
</P>
<P>
The rare relic, first of its kind found in China, is embossed
with colored patterns in the style of the ethnic cultures of
Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
The coffin was found in the square brick chamber of the tomb,
said one expert, adding that the tomb was occupied by Yu Hong, a
foreign affairs official.
</P>
<P>
The coffin was made by joining marble slates carved with scenes
of banquets, performances and hunting. The figures look typical of
ancient Central Asian people.
</P>
<P>
The coffin as its decorations will provide valuable material
for study of the culture and economic exchanges between East and
West in ancient times.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
