<HEADLINE> Indonesian Military Concedes Tensions in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Military (TNI)
conceded that tensions is now rife in the trouble territory of
East Timor, spokesman of the TNI Maj. Gen. Sudradjat told
reporters here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He also said TNI couldn't give security guarantee to those who
would enter the territory.
</P>
<P>
"We of course can't give 100 percent security guarantee to
those intends to enter East Timor, since our troops is not
sufficient to do so," he said, referring to the death of the
London-based Financial Times journalist Sander Thoenes who was
shot to death on Tuesday by unidentified armed-men.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that some 80 Indonesian journalists on Thursday
left Dili, capital of East Timor, because of terror and
intimidation against them following the death of Thoenes.
</P>
<P>
Dozen others are still in Dili, scheduled to leave the
territory on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an Indonesian officer confirmed that the
International Force for East Timor (Interfet) opened fire while
conducting an inspection in some areas in Dili on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, there was a shooting-incident there and it is now being
investigated, involving all the Indonesian Military and Interfet,"
the officer in Dili told the Antara News Agency by phone.
</P>
<P>
There were no casualties in the incident, Antara said. 
</P>
