<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 08:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak: Better to Make Peace With Arab Old Guard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Israel should seek to
strike peace deals with the old guard in the Middle East, such as
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad, said Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
Barak made the remarks in an interview with local daily the
Jerusalem Post, which will publish the full text of the interview
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
It should not wait for a generational change in the Arab world
since old leaders have a unique authority in their societies to
"take big decisions today," while it will take younger leaders
time to consolidate their power, Barak said.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, Assad is the symbol of the revolution in Syria
and he molded the state, while Arafat also in a way is the one who
molded his people, said Barak, adding these leaders hold the sort
of authority and perspective that allow them to make the hard
decisions.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the final-status talks with the Palestinians,
Barak said that if a final-status framework deal does not
succeed, a long-term interim set of understandings might be
reached.
</P>
<P>
Under the so-called Wye Two Accord signed on September 5,
Israel and the Palestinians have to reach a framework agreement on
final-status talks by February and a full lasting peace deal by
next September.
</P>
<P>
Barak called for the immediate construction of a bridge
linking the West Bank and Gaza, which he hopes will be completed
within four years.
</P>
<P>
On the ruling of the High Court of Justice halting physical
pressure against Palestinian suspects, Barak expressed his belief
that the court will permit use of pressure under extraordinary
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the Lebanese issue, Barak said serious Hezbollah
attacks emanating from south Lebanon could lead to a freeze in
talks with Syria. This was the first time that he has linked the
Lebanese issue with Syrian talks.
</P>
<P>
"Terror from Lebanon could put a halt to the process with
Syria," said Barak, adding that he and Assad have a common
interest in curbing Hezbollah terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
He said that once peace is reached with Israel's immediate
neighbors, this will diminish the threat emanating from Iran and
Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
