<HEADLINE> Egypt to Witness Major Social Reforms: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak has said the period ahead will witness major social
transformations to complement the country's all-out economic
reforms, the Egyptian Gazette Newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The starting point lies in working out a comprehensive social
policy based on unequivocal foundations and agreed criteria in
which governmental and non-governmental sectors will be involved,"
Mubarak said on Wednesday at an opening ceremony of a housing
scheme for young people.
</P>
<P>
A national social conference will be held later this year to
draw up the outlines of social development, the president told the
ceremony held at New Sherouk City built near the Cairo-Ismailia
Desert Highway.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, to be attended by governmental and
non-governmental agencies, would also seek to set priorities for a
social renaissance matching economic accomplishments, the
pro-government English-language newspaper quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Since undertaking responsibility, I have been convinced that
the legitimacy of rule itself emanates from the provision of basic
services for citizens and care about society's categories without
discrimination," Mubarak stressed.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak became president in 1981 after the assassination of
former President Anwar Sadat. He was re-elected in 1987 and 1993.
He is set to win a referendum on Sunday to endorse parliament
nomination for a fourth six-year term.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian leader expressed appreciation for the private
sector's initiatives and efforts for the improvement of people's
life.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has invested 45 billion Egyptian pounds (13.24 billion
U.S. dollars) in housing projects, building 2.4 million housing
units, since 1982. The private sector contributed 28 billion
pounds (8.24 billion dollars) to the projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
