<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developing Countries Urged to Play Role in Shaping WTO Direction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Thursday called
upon developing countries to assume a proactive role in shaping
the direction of the World Trade Organization (WTO) to avoid being
trampled by the developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Until developing countries are united, they will not be able to
forge a common position on a number of trade issues that will be
to their advantage, M. Supperamaniam, deputy secretary general of
the Ministry of International Trade and Industry, said here
Thursday at a seminar on "WTO: What it Means to Malaysian
Businessmen" organized by the National Chamber of Commerce and
Industry of Malaysia (NCCIM).
</P>
<P>
"Except for a few vocal ones, many are not participating," he
said, adding developing countries have themselves to blame if big
countries "can do what they want to do" in their trade practices
with developing economies.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that the provision of dispute settlement, one of
the WTO functions, is important especially to developing
countries, he said that through this, developing countries can
challenge the discriminative action of developed countries.
</P>
<P>
He dispelled the notion that the WTO is an institution that
works towards free trade and said: "It doesn't say countries can't
protect domestic industries and in no way does WTO aim to bring
down import duty to zero percent."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, NCCIM President Tajudin Ramli said at a press
conference later that the more developing countries understand the
WTO process and the more they participate in the forum, the better
it will be for everyone.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian business community needs to acquire the knowledge
of WTO rules so that they can take full advantage of the
institution, Tajudin said, adding the ability of the Malaysian
private sector to benefit from the multi-lateral trading system
under WTO rests on their initiative in conveying their views to
the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
