<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Issues $700 Million Eurobonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon has issued its new,
dual-currency sovereign eurobonds worth 700 million U.S. dollars
in the international bond markets, the daily Star reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The issuance, which was officially launched Wednesday, offered
400 million dollars of 10-year bonds at a spread of 440 basis
points over U.S. Treasury bonds and 300 million euros of
seven-year bonds at a spread of 400 basis points over German bonds.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Finance Minister George Korom said the spreads show
Lebanon's ability to borrow much more cheaply than other
emerging-market sovereigns that have tapped international markets
recently.
</P>
<P>
Argentina launched a 500-million, 10-year dollar eurobond in
mid-April at a spread of 623 basis points over U.S. treasuries.
</P>
<P>
The issue also broadens the investor base for Lebanon's
external debts.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors bought 32 percent of the overall issue after
being courted on an extensive roadshow held prior to the launch,
the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Large pension and investment funds in the U.S. and Europe
bought 36 percent of the dollar issue, while foreign
participation in the euro tranche was lower at 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Domestic Lebanese banks, the main buyers of previous sovereign
issues, received 63 percent of the total placement. The remaining
5 percent was placed with Lebanese banks abroad.
</P>
<P>
The new eurobond is the first issue in a 2-billion foreign
borrowing program approved by Parliament in July and it is designed
to reduce the government's reliance on short-term, expensive
Treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
Korom said Lebanon does not plan any more international debt
issues before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has sold more than 3 billion eurobonds since 1994,
often at tighter spreads than those achieved by higher-rated
sovereign borrowers.
</P>
<P>
Its one billion U.S. dollar eurobond in April 1998 was the
largest sovereign issue ever in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Foreign borrowing only accounts for one quarter of Lebanon's
public debt of almost 20 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 09:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jailed Lebanese Student "Spying" for Hezbollah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 23 (Xinhua)n -- Cossette Elias Ibrahim, a
communications student arrested by the South Lebanese Army (SLA)
three weeks ago, has "confessed" to aiding the Hezbollah, local
media reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted Israeli security sources as saying that
Ibrahim "gathered intelligence information for the guerrilla
organization Hezbollah" within Israel's self-proclaimed security
zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim, who also worked occasionally as a freelance
journalist for a variety of Lebanese papers, was arrested by SLA
while visiting her parents in the village of Rameish, in the
central sector of the security zone.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese sources claimed that she was arrested for her negative
descriptions of the Israeli occupying forces in south Lebanon in
her articles.
</P>
<P>
Human rights organizations, as well as the Journalists Without
Frontiers organization, are demanding for her release, and
demonstrations have been staged in Beirut to protest her arrest,
the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim has been reportedly tortured severely at the
SLA-operated El Khayam jail, where she is being held.
</P>
<P>
For its part, the Israeli Defense Force (IDF) has refused to
address the claims, saying that the jail is under SLA control and
the IDF does not involve itself in what goes on there.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the security zone in south Lebanon in 1985,
proclaiming to protect its northern security. The Hezbollah, or
Party of God, has been staging military resistance to the Israeli
military occupation ever since. The SLA is a Lebanese military
group supporting the IDF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
