<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayon Falls Silent While Evacuees Still Flee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- After a jolting blast on
Wednesday noon, Mount Mayon fell back to a deep slumber without
the slightest trace of violence, Philippine News Agency (PNA)
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But evacuees kept flowing in government organized centers,
fearing for their life because of the volcano's erratic character,
PNA said.
</P>
<P>
Close to 500 families are now housed in at least three
evacuation centers, numbering to more or less 3,000 persons.
</P>
<P>
Many of the evacuees come from within and along Mayon's
6-kilometer permanent danger zone, although some come from less
dangerous places.
</P>
<P>
Cedric Daep, chief of the Provincial Disaster Management Office
(PDMO) has warned residents of high risks areas from venturing
near the 6-kilometer zone which is declared a no man's land.
</P>
<P>
Phivolcs maintained Mount Mayon's alert status at level 2.
</P>
<P>
The volcano erupted Wednesday noon, about 11:45 a.m., a preatic
blast stronger than the June 22 explosion and a huge column of ash
laden clouds rose about 7 kilometers up the sky
</P>
<P>
But as soon as the clouds were carried by the northeasterly
winds to Albay province's first district, Mayon fell silent once
more leaving observers puzzled about its real status. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
