<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tremendous Changes Made In Shanghai In Past Half Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Tremendous changes have
taken place in Shanghai in the past half century as the city
turned from a former semi-colony of Western powers into a modern
international metropolis.
</P>
<P>
During an interview, Huang Ju, secretary of the Shanghai
Municipal Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC), said
these huge changes are attributed to the gigantic efforts made by
the CPC over the past 50 years, which have allowed Shanghai to
cast off its humiliating past and take onto the road to a
promising future with brilliant prospects.
</P>
<P>
Starting in 1840, the year in which the "Opium War" broke out,
Shanghai was forced to open to the outside world as a treaty port.
Then, after 1845, foreign powers, including Britain, France and
the United States, continuously snatched up land in Shanghai and
carved them up as concessions.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, the Western-style Bund along the Huangpu River was
first grabbed in the 1920s and 1930s as a concession where foreign
powers set up banks and engaged in many commercial and trade
activities, and the district became known as the Wall Street of
the East. The Bund was looked on as a financial center controlling
old China's economy, as Shanghai served as an abnormal dependency
of the Western nations.
</P>
<P>
Chinese people living in the concessions experienced untold
sufferings not only from ruthless exploitation, but also from
great indignity and humiliations.
</P>
<P>
The founding of New China in 1949, however, ushered into a new
era in Shanghai, which has since taken on a new look.
</P>
<P>
Overseas banks are now allowed to do business in the Shanghai
Bund area along with Chinese banks, and the Bund has become an
attraction for business people and visitors for its row upon row
of Western-style buildings and modern skyscrapers like the 468-
meter-tall Oriental Pearl TV Tower and the 420-meter-tall Jinmao
office building.
</P>
<P>
Fuzhou Road, which was once a British concession, now has more
than 100 book and stationery shops, companies line both its sides,
and it is now a cultural and information center in Shanghai,
instead of the red-light district it was in the past.
</P>
<P>
Hengshan Road, once a French concession, features a combination
of Western and Eastern art and culture. Local residents and
visitors alike can now get the feel of the romantic and
intoxicating ambiance of the Champs Elysees there.
</P>
<P>
All sorts of feelings well up in the Shanghai people when they
reflect on the city's past in the light of its present, and
mention its great change from a humiliated semi-colony to an
independent and open metropolis.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, the city of Shanghai had approved more
than 18,000 overseas-funded projects and had established friendly
relations with 36 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is now striding forward with pride toward a still more
promising future in the new century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Pilot Narrowly Escapes Landing on Highway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A major disaster was
narrowly averted Wednesday night when the control tower at
Israel's Ben Gurion Airport spotted a Russian passenger plane
about to land on a highway next to the airport instead of on the
runway.
</P>
<P>
The controllers were able to contact the pilot at almost last
second and order him to climb. The plane was only 100 meters above
the Jerusalem-Tel Aviv highway at the time and the pilot was
instructed to fly toward the sea before making a second approach,
according to Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Later, the pilot executed the landing at the airport but
ignored the signalers on the ground and committed a series of
safety violations.
</P>
<P>
The crew was questioned by senior officials of Israel Civil
Aviation Authority and the crew focused their debriefing on
the fact that the pilot had a poor command of English.
</P>
<P>
The pilot and the crew were released after being
questioned. The pilot was also examined for possible intoxication,
but emerged with flying colors.
</P>
<P>
The plane, a Tupelov 134, belongs to the BRZ Airlines, which
makes a weekly flight to Israel. About 40 passengers were on the
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The incident caused a delay of about an hour in the scheduled
flight back to Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
