<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0830 GMT, September 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA -- NATO defense ministers ended their two-day informal
meeting in Toronto Wednesday, with U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen urging more spending from member countries.
</P>
<P>
The Kosovo experience is a lesson for NATO which needs more
transport ships and aircraft, improved communications and better
air-ground surveillance, Canadian media quoted the secretary as
saying.
</P>
<P>
NATO had to rely heavily on the American military in its air
strike against Yugoslavia, exposing "deficiencies" in terms of
equipment ranging from surveillance systems to precision-guided
weapons, media reports said. (NATO-Ministerial Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- A Yugoslavian official in charge of Kosovo affairs
Wednesday expressed his dissatisfaction with the current Kosovo
situation, though the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) has been
disbanded into Kosovo Protection Corps (KPC).
</P>
<P>
Zoran Andjelkovich, the President of Provisional Executive
Committee of Kosovo province said the present situation in Kosovo
shows, the KLA has neither been disarmed nor disbanded, it has
just changed its name, Andjelkovich said.
</P>
<P>
The official demanded the UN delegation and international peace-
keeping force stationed in Kosovo to disarm the KLA completely. (
Yugoslavia-Kosovo
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- The Chicago Plan Commission has approved plans
for a residential and commercial skyscraper in downtown Chicago
which developers said would become the world's tallest building,
according to a report reaching here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The proposed building would be 1,550 feet (472 meters) tall at
the roof line, with two 450-foot (137-meter) antennas, much taller
than the current world's tallest building -- the CN Tower in
Toronto, standing at 1,815 feet (463 meters). (US-Skyscraper)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- A moderate earthquake measuring 4.2 in magnitude
rattled Northern California on Wednesday, but no damage or
injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
Pat Jorgenson, spokeswoman for the U.S. Geological Survey said
the quake happened shortly before 3:30 p.m. and lasted only a few
seconds.
</P>
<P>
It was centered along the Rodgers Creek fault, about 10
kilometers northeast of Rohnert Park, a small city 60 kilometers
north of San Francisco, the largest metropolis in Northern
California.  (US-Quake)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) leader
Abdullah Ocalan has called on a group of his militants to
surrender to the government to show their sincerity in making
peace.
</P>
<P>
"I call on a PKK group to come to Turkey, with their arms, to
join the democratic republic as an expression of goodwill and to
prove that the PKK is not an obstacle to democratic reforms," the
imprisoned Kurdish rebel leader said in a statement published by
the local Daily News Thursday. (Turkey-PKKE)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The International Force for East Timor (Interfet)
opened fire while conducting an inspection in some areas in Dili,
East Timor, but it is not clear to whom the shoot was aimed and
what reasons were behind it.
</P>
<P>
A joint team has been deployed to the field to prevent a
misunderstanding between the Indonesian Military and Interfet, The
temporary report said.
</P>
<P>
There were no casualties in the incident, the report added. (
Indonesia-East Timor-Shooting) 
</P>
