<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Given Deadline on Power Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KAMPALA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni has been given a deadline to enact the electricity bill
to facilitate the construction of a power station at the
controversial site of Bujagali in Jinja, 80 kilometers east of the
capital city Kampala.
</P>
<P>
This deadline was contained in a letter to the president by
U.S. Secretary of Trade Denis William and the letter was read to
MPs in the Natural Resources Committee at the State House
Wednesday, the Monitor newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
If the law is delayed beyond the end of September, it will
spoil U.S.- Uganda relations, the letter warned, urging Kampala to
*6"
enact the electricity bill quickly to allow a U.S. company to
generate power on the Nile River.
</P>
<P>
MPs in the committee, however, defied the warning from the
United States, saying that Uganda's Parliament is not an arm of
Washington, a legislator who attended the impromptu meeting was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
AES Nile Power, a U.S. company, planned to invest 450 million
dollars in building a hydroelectric power station on the Nile
River, a project expected to end load-shedding in Uganda whose
power demand is increasing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
Those who support the project are focused on the possible
economic, social and tourist advantages, while the opponents,
including environmental groups, argue that the project would
destroy Uganda's natural heritage and environment.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the Uganda Electricity Board is the sole supplier
of electricity in Uganda. It has an installed capacity of 180
megawatts at the Owen Falls Hydropower Station against an
estimated current peak demand of 250 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
Only about five percent of the population in Uganda has access
to electricity, of which 70 percent is in the three major cities
of Kampala, Entebbe and Jinja. 
</P>
</TEXT>
