<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Jordan Cracks Down on Hamas to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has closed the Amman
office of the Palestinian Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) and
arrested 15 of its members on national security charges in an
apparent move to promote the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The crackdown upon Hamas came at a time when Israel and the
Palestinians are making progress on the implementation of the Wye
River peace accord and are heading for the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
Hamas is known as a radical militant Palestinian organization
which opposes the peace process between the Jewish state and the
Palestinians, and it has reportedly carried out several deadly
attacks on Israeli civilians in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
The government has long tolerated the presence of the Hamas
office in Amman and its activities because of its many
sympathizers among the predominantly Palestinian population of the
desert kingdom.
</P>
<P>
However, the tolerance came to an end on August 30 when police
closed the Hamas office, arrested 12 of its members and issued
arrest warrants against four of its leaders who were then on a
visit to Iran.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, police also detained Khaled Mashaal and Ibrahim
Ghosheh, two Jordanian citizens but the most senior Hamas leaders
based in Amman, and deported another senior Hamas leader Abu
Marzuk who held a Yemeni passport.
</P>
<P>
The move was viewed as a preemptive measure to pave the way, to
some extent, for the critical and yet vulnerable peace process
between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Charges against the Hamas members included holding military
exercises in Jordanian territory as part of its campaigns on
Israel and illegal possession of arms and weapons, which the
government said had violated Jordan's national interest.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been a staunch supporter and broker for the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process, and Amman viewed its 1994
peace treaty with Israel as one of the pillars of its foreign
policies.
</P>
<P>
The Hamas movement still stands for a holy war "to liberate
all Palestinian territories" to establish an Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
The fundamental difference means that Hamas activities will
be strictly prohibited in the foreseeable future, at least until
some tangible progresses are made in the Israeli-Palestinian track
of the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mashaal, political chief of Hamas who was arrested on
Wednesday, said his arrest was politically motivated during an
interview with the Paris-based Radio Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
``This is a political issue caused by pressures from the
United States, the Zionist entity (Israel) and the Palestinian
Authority on Jordan to muzzle Hamas during the final status
negotiations," said Mashaal.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian officials said Mashaal and other Hamas members will
be tried under the Jordanian law on charges of engaging in
illegal political activities in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
If convicted, they might face a one-year prison term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
