<HEADLINE> Cambodian PM Returns from New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Prime Minister
Hun Sen returned home Thursday after nearly one-month three-nation
trip to Canada, Cuba and the United States.
</P>
<P>
At a brief press conference held at the Pochentong
International Airport, Sok An, minister of the Council of
Ministers, told reporters that the prime minister's three-nation
trip was very success.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the trial of Khmer Rouge, Sok An reaffirmed the
government's stance to respect Cambodia's national sovereignty put
forward in a memo that Hun Sen delivered to U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan on September 16.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the memo gave the United Nations only
three options: either appoint some foreign judges and prosecutors
to a Cambodian existing court, provide legal advice without direct
participation or "end involvement of the United Nations, let
Cambodia itself to do it in accordance with its own laws.
</P>
<P>
Sok An said the Cambodian government is waiting the answer of
the United Nations, but the preparation of the trial will
continue. "It should not be delayed indefinitely," he stressed.
But there's not enough time to do it this year, he added.
</P>
<P>
During his week-long visit to Cuba, Hun Sen held official talks
with President Fidel Castro and toured Cuba's Center of Genetic
Engineering and Biotechnology in Havana.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed a memorandum of understanding for
economic, scientific and technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In New York, Hun Sen met with U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
on the issue of trying Khmer Rouge leaders, but no compromise was
reached. He also delivered his first-ever address as prime
minister before the U.N. General Assembly on Tuesday that focused
on economy and poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
Before the Cuba trip, Hun Sen also attend the VIII Summit of
heads of state and government of Francophonie held in Moneton, Mew
Brunswick, Canada, from September 3 to 5 at the invitation of his
Canada counterpart Jean Chretien.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied Hun Sen on the visits were Foreign Minister Hor
Namhong, Minister of the Council of Ministers Sok An, and other
senior officials of the Royal Government and the Ministry of
Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
