<HEADLINE> PKK Leader Urges Followers to Surrender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) leader Abdullah Ocalan has called on a group
of his militants to surrender to the government to show their
sincerity in making peace.
</P>
<P>
"I call on a PKK group to come to Turkey, with their arms, to
join the democratic republic as an expression of goodwill and to
prove that the PKK is not an obstacle to democratic reforms," the
imprisoned Kurdish rebel leader said in a statement published by
the local Daily News Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the statement delivered by Ocalan's lawyers
as saying that "this step by the PKK would be a symbolic step for
a peaceful and democratic solution. Such a step would be very
important in order to show that our decision to give up the armed
struggle is earnest."
</P>
<P>
"We expect the attention and assistance of the state and
society," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan prepared the statement at a meeting with his lawyers on
the island of Imrali in western Turkey on Monday, where he is the
sole prisoner.
</P>
<P>
The PKK announced last month that it was pulling PKK militants
out of Turkey to pave the way for peace.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has claimed that about one-quarter of an estimated
1,500 militants have been pulled out of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military has dismissed the move as a tactical
ploy, saying the PKK was retreating to spend winter in nearby
bases as it usually did at this time of the year.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 a war for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey, which has claimed over
37,000 lives. 
</P>
