<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Tool for Timber Developed in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A hitman will soon be
roaming forests in New Zealand. However, the target won't be
people but felled logs on the forest floor awaiting their fate.
</P>
<P>
The Hitman is a new acoustic tool to assess the stiffness and
fiber properties of tree stems and logs using soundwaves.
</P>
<P>
Jointly developed by New Zealand's Industry Research and Carter
Holt Harvey, one of the biggest forestry companies in the country,
the tool is designed to help an operator determine where the cuts
should be made on a stem to maximize the usefulness of each
section.
</P>
<P>
Stiffness and fiber properties affect the wood's performance in
construction and pulp and paper applications. Different uses have
widely different dollar values.
</P>
<P>
"There's a lot of natural variation within any stand of trees.
The advantage of the Hitman is that we can accurately sort the
logs in terms of strength and fiber properties and then maximize
the total value of the forest," Marco Lausberg of Carter Holt
Harvey was quoted as saying by the latest issue of "Innovate"
published by the Industrial Research.
</P>
<P>
The Hitman tool comprises a small palm-sized calculator
connected by a short cable to an acceleration sensor. The
calculator houses sensing electronics and the equivalent of a 386
computer, and the whole device can be hooked on to an operator's
belt or clothing.
</P>
<P>
By holding the sensor against the cut end of the stem and
hitting this same end with a hammer the operator sends a soundwave
down the tree. The soundwave bounces off the other end of the stem
and the reverberation time is measured by the sensor.
</P>
<P>
The reverberation is a direct measure of the log's stiffness.
The faster the soundwave, the stiffer the tree is and vice-versa.
</P>
<P>
"The device has quite a lot of intelligence built into it to
interpret bounce times under different conditions, like whether
the log is on the ground or in a stack, and can cope with logs up
to 35 meters," Lausberg said.
</P>
<P>
The Hitman is powered by a single 9-volt battery which should
last for more than one operator's shift.
</P>
<P>
Future work in this field could lead to the development of
sonic or ultrasonic methods for assessing trees before they are
even felled, "Innovate" said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wellington Sees Increasing Sexual Disease Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's Wellington
region sees increasing sexual disease cases this year.
</P>
<P>
The Evening Post, a Wellington-based newspaper, Thursday
reported that Wellington doctors are "alarmed at an upsurge in
sexual diseases in the region and fear an epidemic".
</P>
<P>
The Wellington Independent Practice Association (WIPA) has
noticed a 400 percent rise in HIV cases in the region over the
past six months and a 50 percent rise in cases of gonorrhoea, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
"Local laboratory Medlab has found a new gonorrhoea case once a
week on average this year compared with a new case every three
weeks last year. And last week three new cases were diagnosed," it
added.
</P>
<P>
The genital herpes and warts rates in the Wellington region
have also been above the national average for the last two years,
according to the Evening Post.
</P>
<P>
It quoted WIPA sexual health physician Margaret Sparrow as
saying that she is "alarmed at the cases because, if not stemmed,
there would be an epidemic." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
