<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Cuts State Corporation Spenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Extravagant foreign travel,
huge and uncontrolled expense accounts and free spending in
Kenya's state corporations are to severely cut back, local media
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The new tough measures are part of the government's efforts to
cut spending and improve services, Richard Leakey, Civil Service
head, told a meeting attended by heads of parastatals and
government departments, permanent secretaries and other top
public officials held here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Leakey warned the parastatal heads who have run down their
institutions or were implicated in corruption will be sacked, and
they will also be made to repay money misappropriated during
their tenure.
</P>
<P>
With immediate effect, parastatal chiefs travelling outside
their stations will have their expense accounts severely cut, the
civil service head said.
</P>
<P>
Official foreign trips to attend conferences or workshops will
be limited to only one official for each parastatal or
supervising ministry, who will travel economy class, Leakey said,
adding that those who want to travel first class will have to pay
the difference in the price of the ticket from their own pocket.
</P>
<P>
Leakey urged the state corporation heads to ensure their
operations must match in efficiency and match those in the
private sector.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the National Social Security Fund and
National Hospital Insurance Fund, Kenya Railways and Kenya Ports
Authority are among some of the big corporations which had
previously been cited as havens for corruption and mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
