<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Leading China's Modernization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Province adjacent
Hong Kong will lead China in approaching the country's
modernization target because of its pioneer role in reform and
opening, said provincial Governor Lu Ruihua in a recent exclusive
interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"Guangdong has witnessed dramatic changes during the past 50
years, which has transformed it from a backward province to the
country's fastest-growing economic powerhouse," said Lu.
</P>
<P>
The GDP growth in the southern province last year tripled that
in 1978 to reach 793.7 billion yuan, accounting for 10 percent of
the country's total.
</P>
<P>
It also leads the country in tax revenue, the use of foreign
investment, exports, retail sales and personal bank deposits.
</P>
<P>
Lu attributes Guangdong's success to the good use of its
proximity to Hong Kong while pioneering the country's market-
oriented reform.
</P>
<P>
Deng Xiaoping, the late general architect of China's reform and
opening up policy, said in 1992 that Guangdong will catch up with
Asia's four "Little Dragons," Hong Kong, Taiwan, Singapore and the
Republic of Korea, by the next century.
</P>
<P>
The present Chinese government and State President Jiang Zemin
pin high hope on Guangdong and expect the province's three
economic zones and the economic belt of the Pearl River Delta to
take a faster pace in realizing the country's modernization target
in 2010.
</P>
<P>
To that end, Guangdong has a strategy for developing an export-
oriented economy through science and education and continuing a
sustainable economic growth, said Lu.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong's practice will provide experience for other parts of
the country to follow and it will not let the Chinese leadership
and people down, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Worries About Incomplete Y2K Readiness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Presidential
Y2K Commission has shown worry about the incomplete Y2K readiness
of some key sectors and government agencies as the government-set
deadline for Y2K compliance is drawing up.
</P>
<P>
Y2K Commission Chairman Amable Aguiluz told reporters Thursday
that only 80 percent of firms and government agencies were Y2K
ready as of last month.
</P>
<P>
While the commission wants to 100 percent readiness by the
pending deadline of September 30, he predicts that "it will only
be 88 percent at the end of the deadline set."
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the commission reported only 200 of the more than
18,000 companies and government agencies belonging to the
so-called seven mission-critical sectors are Y2K ready.
</P>
<P>
The seven mission-critical sectors include finance,
telecommunications, transportation, utilities, health care,
manufacturing and government service.
</P>
<P>
Aguiluz said the commission will go after companies and
government agencies which do not comply with the Y2K law.
</P>
<P>
All government agencies and private companies are required to
submit Y2K disclosure statements every month. Those which fail to
do so are presumed to be non-Y2K compliant.
</P>
<P>
Those who could not be Y2K-compliant on September 30 will be
subjected to all the sanctions that are provided in the Y2K law,
Aguiluz stressed.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, heads of the government agencies face
administrative charges, while private companies may be charged
under the Civil Code for damages related to the bug. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
