<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Pilot Narrowly Escapes Landing on Highway in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A major disaster was
narrowly averted Wednesday night when the control tower at the Ben
Gurion Airport spotted a Russian passenger plane about to land at
the Tel Aviv-Jerusalem Highway next to the airport, instead of on
the runway.
</P>
<P>
The controllers were able to contact the pilot at almost the
last second and order him to climb. The plane was only 100 meters
above the highway at the time and the pilot was instructed to fly
toward the sea before making a second approach, according to
Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Later, the pilot executed the landing at the airport but
ignored the signalers on the ground and committed a series of
safety violations.
</P>
<P>
The crew was questioned by senior officials of Israel's Civil
Aviation Authority and the crew focused their debriefing on the
fact that the pilot had a poor command of English.
</P>
<P>
The pilot and the crew were released after being questioned.
The pilot was also examined for possible intoxication, but emerged
with flying colors.
</P>
<P>
The plane, a Tupelov 134, belongs to the BRZ Airlines, which
makes a weekly flight to Israel. About 40 passengers were on the
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The incident caused a delay of about an hour in the scheduled
flight back to Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
