<HEADLINE> U.S. Hawaiian Airlines Buys 13 Boeing 717s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Hawaiian Airlines said
Wednesday it has agreed to buy 13 Boeing 717-200 airplanes for 430
million U.S. dollars, according to a report reaching here late in
the day.
</P>
<P>
The nation's 12th-largest carrier said the order eventually
will replace its entire fleet of 15 inter-island aircraft, with
all of the new planes flying by the end of 2001. Hawaiian also has
an option to buy seven more airplanes before 2005 for an
additional 200 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Hawaiian Airlines will be able to increase customers by flying
more flights because the new aircraft are more efficient and less
costly to operate.
</P>
<P>
"This is a major investment in the future of the company,"
Hawaiian president Paul Casey said. "It underscores our commitment
to the future of inter-island travel."
</P>
<P>
Launched as the MD-95 in October 1995, the airplane was renamed
the Boeing 717-200 after McDonnell Douglas was merged into Boeing
two years ago. The first of the new models, produced in Long Beach,
California, is scheduled for delivery Thursday to AirTran Airways
</P>
<P>
Hawaiian would be the fifth airline to order the 717. The
Hawaiian Airlines order brings the total number of orders for the
model to 128, with options taken on 117 more.  
</P>
</TEXT>
