<HEADLINE> U.S. to Accept Passports of Macao SAR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. official stationed in
Hong Kong has announced that the United States will accord full
acceptance to the new passports of the future Macao Special
Administrative Region (SAR) of China.
</P>
<P>
"Macao travelers will continue to enjoy the same favorable
treatment that Hong Kong travelers receive," Michael Klosson, U.S.
consul general in Hong Kong, said here Wednesday night at a
reception attended by Macao's senior government officials and
social celebrities.
</P>
<P>
A Macao Policy Act, now before the U.S. Congress, states that
after December 20, the U.S. should continue to play an active role
in maintaining Macao's confidence and prosperity, unique cultural
heritage, and the mutually beneficial ties between the people of
the United States and the people of Macao, Michael Klosson said.
</P>
<P>
The consul general also noted that the United States wants to
build on economic and commercial links with Macao.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. currently receives nearly 50 percent of Macao's
exports. We hope to continue to serve as an important market for
Macao exporters, but are also eager to expand U.S. sales here,"
Klosson said.
</P>
<P>
"Macao's infrastructural development has created and we hope
will continue to create opportunities for U.S. trade and
investment," the U.S. diplomat said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
