<HEADLINE> US Pledges to Exert Influence Over Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. has pledged to
exert its influence to accelerate the peace process in Cyprus,
Cyprus' Government Spokesman Michalis Papapetrou said in New
York Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, Cyprus President Clerides reiterated his readiness to
participate in talks the U.N. chief is expected to invite next
month, Papapetrou said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman described the meeting as constructive, saying
they discussed efforts to resume intercommunal talks under the
auspices of the U.N. Secretary General in a bid to achieve a
breakthrough and reach a Cyprus settlement.
</P>
<P>
"All aspects were examined and the Greek Cypriot side stressed
the need to proceed with the implementation of U.N. Security
Council resolution 1250 which calls for the resumption of talks
without preconditions, " he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Clerides reiterated that "the Greek Cypriot
side is ready to participate in these talks on an absolutely equal
footing."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the international community has been trying to
bring the two sides to negotiations for reunification through a
bicommunal settlement. But no tangible progress has been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash has said he will not
attend talks unless his breakaway state in northern Cyprus is
recognized.
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou said Albright did not indicate whether or not
Denktash will accept a U.N. talks invitation, but the sooner
the invitations go out, the sooner the answer will be known.
</P>
<P>
He said whatever form any negotiations take, they will not
be shuttle talks.
</P>
<P>
"What we need is a process of more substantial talks," he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
