<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang's Visit to Britain a New Milestone: Chinese Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese ambassador to Britain,
Ma Zhengang, said here Tuesday that Chinese President Jiang Zemin'
s state visit to Britain next month will be a new milestone in
Sino-British relations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a banquet held to celebrate the 50th anniversary of
the founding of the People's Republic of China which falls on
October 1, Ma said, the Sino-British relations have been further
developed in recent years with increased exchanges and cooperation
in various sectors.
</P>
<P>
He added that long-term, sound and stable comprehensive
cooperative ties between China and Britain will not only benefit
the peoples of the two countries, but will also be in the common
interests of the peoples all over the world.
</P>
<P>
"Taiwan is an inseparable part of China and the reunification
of the motherland is a strong common aspiration of all Chinese
people," he said, "We will adhere to the basic principles of '
peaceful reunification' and 'one country, two systems', and firmly
safeguard China's sovereignty and territorial integrity."
</P>
<P>
British Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott said that since the
founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949, China has
become a major power with economic, political and cultural
importance, and has been playing an important role in world events.
</P>
<P>
During the Asian economic crisis, China showed great courage in
resisting the easy option of devaluation. The decision was vital
to the stability of Hong Kong, the Asian region and vital to
stability for the global economy, Prescott said.
</P>
<P>
"That is why we all want to see China playing a full part in
the world's economy and why we fully support and welcome her
entry into the World Trade Organization," he added.
</P>
<P>
Since the return of Hong Kong to China in 1997, the deputy
prime minister said, the British-Chinese relations have been
strengthened and become matured.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin's state visit to Britain next
month, the first ever by a Chinese head of state, will be "an
important and highly symbolic occasion for the strong partnership
that we are building between our two countries," he added.
</P>
<P>
Among the 600 guests attending the banquet were Margaret
Beckett, Britain's lord president of the council and leader of the
house of commons, Baroness Jay, the lord privy seal and leader of
the house of lords, Chris Smith, secretary of culture, media and
sports as well as former Prime Minister Edward Heath. 
</P>
</TEXT>
