<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500, GMT September 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA -- Angola is in heavy debt to Portugal, with the amount
of the official debts reaching 679 million U.S. dollars by the end
of 1998, official news agency Angop reported on Wednesday. (
Angola-Debt)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) said the
macroeconomic performance of the crisis-hit economies in Asia has
continued to improve in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Positive GDP growth is expected in almost all countries in the
region in 1999 as a whole, with projections in some cases revised
up substantially, the IMF said in its World Economic Outlook
released here Wednesday. (IMF-Asia-Recovery)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and India on Wednesday signed a memorandum of
understanding aimed at bolstering cooperation in upgrading Egypt's
software industry. (Egypt-India-Memo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The International Monetary Fund released the
World Economic Outlook here today, predicting a global economic
growth of about 3 percent in 1999, 0.7 percent higher than that
projected in May this year. The global growth rate for 2000 would
be 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Global economic and financial conditions have improved markedly
after the turbulence in emerging markets in 1997-98, which gave
rise to fears of a widespread credit crunch and global recession,
and most of the economies recently in crisis have begun to recover,
said the IMF report. (IMF-World Economy-Improvement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's global merchandise trade surplus posted a year-
on-year fall of 22.6 percent in August, marking the fifth straight
month of decline, the Finance Ministry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The surplus plunged to 689.4 billion yen (5.9 billion dollars)
as a stronger yen held back exports, the ministry said in a
preliminary report. (Japan-Trade-Surplus) 
</P>
