<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manufacturing Output Down 4.6 Percent in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' manufacturing
output, hurt by Asia's economic turmoil, decreased by 4.6 percent
year-on-year in July while net sales declined by 5.8 percent, the
government said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, existing capacity continued to operate at low
levels, the National Statistics Office said, adding that
responding establishments operating below 70 percent of capacity
were 43.7 percent in July compared to 37.9 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
July is the second consecutive month posting manufacturing
output slowdown after a three-month increase starting in March,
which was the first month since January 1998 that the volume of
production index did not fall.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers of basic metals, non-metallic mineral products,
petroleum, paper and paper products, furniture and fixtures, food,
beverages, tobacco, textiles and wearing apparel suffered declines
in both production and sales in July.
</P>
<P>
The government attributed the fall to the prevailing weak
construction and consumer demand leading to the shutdown of some
machineries and plants.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Rubber, transport equipment and electrical machinery
manufacturers managed to turn in positive performances in both
production and sales in July.
</P>
<P>
Separately, an index measuring the value of production
decreased 0.7 percent year-on-year in July, after rising 2.3
percent in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
