<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electronic Banking to be Introduced in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Standard Chartered Bank of
London is going to launch electronic banking services for windows
(EBSW) in Nepal within a week, The Kathmandu Post reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bank's manager in Nepal Madhu Aryal told the paper
Wednesday that the aim of doing so is to facilitate the bank's
international electronic banking services for its customers in
Nepal and abroad.
</P>
<P>
EBSW is a package for a comprehensive banking solution for
corporate and financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Aryal said that his bank will also provide SWIFT-based software
to Nepal Bank Limited and Rastriya Banijya Bank free of cost in
order to improve their efficiency.
</P>
<P>
After introducing the system, these banks can easily see their
accounts opened in any banks all over the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, those banks that have access to such electronic
banking services would enable their customers to open up letter of
credit. The system does not require money in carrying out banking
activities at home an abroad, Aryal added.
</P>
<P>
EBSW support full range of cash management reporting and
transaction initiation needs that provides secure, reliable and
effective link between the bank and its accounts anywhere in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The system enables account holders to view account details,
balance details, statements and history information quickly and
easily.
</P>
<P>
Through EBSW, anyone can have access to the full range of
domestic and cross-border transaction initiation including
electronic funds transfer as well as paper-based options such as
drafts.
</P>
<P>
Standard Chartered was the first foreign bank to start
operation in Nepal 20 years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
