<HEADLINE> Malaysia's New King Officially Installed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's new King
Sultan Salahuddin Abdul Aziz Shah, upon his ascendance to the
throne on Thursday, urged Malaysians to always uphold and respect
the system of Parliamentary democracy to ensure the country's
continued stability and progress.
</P>
<P>
Sultan Salahuddin Abdul Aziz Shah was officially installed at a
traditional ceremony held at the National Palace here as the 11th
Supreme Head of State (paramount ruler) under the country's unique
constitutional monarchy.
</P>
<P>
At the glittering ceremony, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad
read out the proclamation of installation and the Grand
Chamberlain Zubir Ali then presented the short-sword of state and
the oath letter to the King.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his installation, the king said the ability of the
various races to live in peace and harmony while respecting the
provisions in the Constitution is a matter of national pride.
</P>
<P>
"The special attributes of this multiracial country are its
eastern values, high ethics, courtesy, politeness and preserving
family harmony," he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia practiced a system of government based on
Parliamentary Democracy and Constitutional Monarchy as provided
for in the Constitution, he said, adding "I am happy this system
has ensured the country's peace and progress."
</P>
<P>
Wanting his subjects to cherish racial harmony and strive with
determination for Malaysia's continued peace, progress and
prosperity, Sultan Salahuddin said Malaysians should always
cooperate with the Government in its efforts to raise productivity
and improve the competitiveness of the country.
</P>
<P>
"The mischievous attempts by certain groups to erode people's
confidence in the Government should be opposed to the end," the
King said, hoping his subjects of various races will not be
influenced or made use of by irresponsible groups.
</P>
<P>
"Our duty now is to ensure the country's full economic
recovery, " the King said.
</P>
<P>
He hoped Malaysians in their pursuit of progress would not
neglect eastern values, discipline and loyalty to King and
country.
</P>
<P>
Sultan Salahuddin also expressed the hope that the general
election to be held in the country would proceed smoothly and
safely without any unpleasant incidents.
</P>
<P>
The general election is due by the first half of 2000 but there
are wide speculations that the polls would be held any time this
year.
</P>
<P>
The new King advised his people not to allow themselves to fall
prey to values which sacrificed the larger interests of the
community.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his thanks to the government and people for their
expression of loyalty and congratulations on the occasion of his
installation.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that I will be able to discharge my duties and
responsibilities entrusted to me with wisdom, justice and
fairness," the new monarch said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
