<HEADLINE> Swiss Drug Giant, Partners Fined Record Sum of Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Swiss drug giant F. Hoffmann-
Laroche Ltd. and four other multinationals Wednesday were fined a
record sum of money up to more than 88 million Canadian dollars (
about 59 million U.S. dollars) in Canada.
</P>
<P>
Hoffmann-LaRoche pleaded guilty in the Federal Court in Toronto
for conspiring to fix vitamin prices in Canada with BASF AG, Rhone
Poulenc SA and two Japanese companies Daiichi Pharmaceuticals Ltd.
and Eisi, according to Local media.
</P>
<P>
Hoffmann-LaRoche was hit with a fine of 50.9 million Canadian
dollars (about 37.5 million U.S. dollars), while the other four
companies were subjected to fines ranging from 2 million (about 1.
3 million U.S. dollars) to 19 million (about 12.7 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Justice Department blew the lid off the scam in May,
leading to the continued investigation by the Canadian Competition
Bureau, the media said.
</P>
<P>
Roche and the BASF had previously agreed to pay about 670
million U.S. dollars in penalty in the U.S. 
</P>
</TEXT>
