<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former U.S. Ambassador to China on Cross-Straits Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. Ambassador to
Beijing James R. Sasser has warned that any attempt in Taiwan to
upset the present one-China policy will be detrimental to the U.S.
interests as well as to all parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
Sasser said in a recent interview here with Xinhua that the one-
China policy has served all parties concerned very well for almost
30 years, including the Chinese mainland, Taiwan, the United
States and the people in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
"To try to upset this relationship now and try to modify or
reframe it is not in the best interests of anyone, certainly not
in the interests of the United States. It's to hurt," said Sasser,
who was sworn in as U.S. Ambassador to the People's Republic of
China on January 10, 1996, and back home after completing his
tenure last June.
</P>
<P>
Cross-straits relations have plunged into an abyss since Lee
Teng-hui put out the "state-to-state" fallacy last July in an
apparent bid to shred off the one-China policy as a major step
towards a de facto independence of the island.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that there would be some pulling back from the so-
called 'state-to-state' relations by the authorities of Taiwan,"
Sasser said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the Taiwanese authorities "would make a great
mistake if they think the United States and the U.S. military is
going to back them no matter what sort of problems are at issue."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government and the American people don't want to be
pulled into some sort of conflict in the Taiwan Straits by the
Taiwanese authorities, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has insisted that the dispute
between Taiwan and the Chinese mainland should be resolved between
themselves, he said.
</P>
<P>
China has always embraced a peaceful reunification under the "
one country, two systems" formula, but does not rule out the use
of force as a last resort to prevent Taiwan's separation from
China.
</P>
<P>
The former ambassador witnessed in the last couple of years
heightening moments as the heads of state of the two countries
exchanged official visits in 1997 and 1998, as well as low ebbs
this year following the release of Cox report and the U.S.-led
NATO bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador dismissed the Cox report, which smeared China
with nuclear espionage, as "overstated" and "not well researched."
</P>
<P>
He described the Cox report as having "a strong smell of
partisan politics" as well as "racist tones," because it aims just
at Chinese American scientists who work at Los Alamos National
Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
"As time goes on, the Cox report will become more and more
discredited," Sasser said.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador also urged the Clinton administration to close
an agreement on China's access to the World Trade Organization (
WTO) by the end of this year as agreed upon by the two sides when
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji paid a visit here last spring.
</P>
<P>
Sasser pointed out that the growing economic ties between the
two countries are "very strong" and "very powerful."
</P>
<P>
"When there're difficulties in our relationship on the
political front, the economic ties have become the things that
kept the ship stay afloat," he added.
</P>
<P>
Sasser also rejected the so-called China threat from a
historical point of view, saying that Chinese history over the
past few centuries has proved that the Chinese nation is neither
militaristic nor expansionist.
</P>
<P>
"I don't anticipate it (China) will become a power which will
try to infringe upon its neighbors, or try to impose its will on
other countries against their will," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
