<HEADLINE> Myanmar Factories to Undergo Modernization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar leader Senior-General
Than Shwe has stressed the need for factories and plants in the
country to undergo modernization and renovation.
He also said that private industries, which are only small-scale
ones, need to be upgraded into medium-scale and then into
large-scale ones.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with industrialists in Mandalay Industrial Zone in
central Myanmar on Tuesday, Than Shwe, who is the country's
chairman of the State Peace and Development Council, said the
government is providing assistance to private industrialists,
adding that without the government's help it is impossible for
them to develop, the official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The authorities have made allotments for 4,000 more
industrialists to engage in the activities in the Mandalay zone,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The authorities have also planned to extend low-interest loans
to industrialists beginning October 1 this year and to cut the
rate of revenues as part of its measures to encourage the
industrialists for the activities, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Mandalay Industrial Zone is one of the 18 of its kind so far
established in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent issue of Myanmar Business News, there
registered 36,275 private industrial enterprises in Myanmar at the
end of 1998, of which 4,075 are medium-sized enterprises, while
30,650 are small-sized ones.
</P>
<P>
Of these, 7,980 are located in Mandalay, topping all other
states and divisions, followed by Yangon with 5,396 and Bago with
4,514.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar's industrial sector
accounts for 9.2 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP),
standing as the second largest contributor to the GDP after
agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
