<HEADLINE> Australia Army Plans to Recruit Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 23 (Xinhua) --The Australian army is
planning to recruit reserves to support its mission in East Timor,
a military spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"The rotation requires an expansion of the current force. That
will be achieved by fleshing out the 7th Brigade and increasing
its full-time component," Australian Defense Force spokesman
Colonel Duncan Lewis was quoted Thursday by the Australian
Associated Press (AAP) as telling reporters.
The 7th Task Force, an infantry brigade stationed in Brisbane, is
currently made up mostly of part-timers.
According to the spokesman, the Australian defense force holds
only about 23,000 standing troops and is not enough to rotate the
panned force of 4,500 in East Timor.
The Australian government has promised to meet the cost of
raising another brigade of troops to ensure Australia can
maintain its 4,500-strong force in East Timor. 
</P>
