<HEADLINE> NATO Defense Ministers End Toronto Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- NATO defense ministers ended
their two-day informal meeting in Toronto Wednesday, with U.S.
Defense Secretary William Cohen urging more spending from member
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Kosovo experience is a lesson for NATO which needs more
transport ships and aircraft, improved communications and better
air-ground surveillance, Canadian media quoted the secretary as
saying.
</P>
<P>
NATO had to rely heavily on the American military in its air
strike against Yugoslavia, exposing "deficiencies" in terms of
equipment ranging from surveillance systems to precision-guided
weapons, media reports said.
</P>
<P>
Some member countries would simply "have to spend more" to
close the technology gap with the U.S., Cohen told the meeting,
adding he wanted NATO to set priority targets by December, when
ministers will work out a timetable for improvements.
</P>
<P>
NATO ministers agreed earlier to cut down troops in Bosnia from
the current 30,000 to 21,000. NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana said Tuesday that a cut in peacekeeping forces in the
Balkans is possible due to the improved security in the region.
</P>
<P>
This was the last meeting of NATO defense ministers attended by
Solana in the capacity of secretary-general. British Defense
Minister George Robertson will replace him as NATO chief next
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
