the Communist Party of China (CPC) concluded yesterday in Beijing
after four days of deliberation.
</P>
<P>
The plenum mapped out the major targets of State-owned
enterprises reform and development through the year of 2010 and
the guiding principles that must be upheld.
</P>
<P>
The plenum also decided to appoint Hu Jintao as vice-chairman
of the Central Military Commission.
</P>
<P>
-- The paper front-paged Chinese President Jiang Zemin's speech
at a meeting marking the 50th anniversary of the founding of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference yesterday.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin has said that the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) should and is
fully capable of playing a greater role in the affairs of the
nation.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks during a speech yesterday at a meeting
marking the 50th anniversary of the founding of the CPPCC.
</P>
<P>
-- The Fourth Plenum of the 15th Central Committee of the CPC
decided to expel Xu Yunhong, an alternate member of CPC Central
Committee, from the body.
</P>
<P>
The decision was based on an investigation report from the
Communist Party of China's Central Commission for Discipline
Inspection.
</P>
<P>
Xu, also a standing committee member of the CPC Zhejiang
Provincial Committee and secretary of the Ningbo City Party
Committee, took advantage of his position and helped repeatedly at
his wife's and his son's requests to obtain permission and loans
for businesses in exchange for a large amount of money and gifts
worth more than 6.9 million yuan (about 830,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The plenum decided that Xu is stripped of all his posts and his
party membership, and his case will be handled by judicial
departments according to legal procedures.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The paper front-paged a profile of Hu Jintao, the newly
appointed vice-chairman of the Central Military Commission.
</P>
<P>
-- The Red Cross Society of China and many other mainland
organizations expressed concern over and offered help for the
victims of the massive earthquake that hit Taiwan Tuesday morning.
