<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Offers Aid to Quake-hit Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has offered
assistance worth one million baht (25,000 U.S. dollars) to Taiwan
province of China where a strong earthquake killed over 1,700
people Tuesday, Foreign Ministry spokesman Don Pramudwinai said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the Thai government had approved the
assistance in cash and necessary supplies on a humanitarian basis.
</P>
<P>
A medical team, including doctors and nurses from the Thai Red
Cross, has already been sent to Taiwan, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai had sent a
condolence to the Taiwanese people, expressing deep regret on
behalf of the Thai people over the deaths, casualties and damages
occurred.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake, measured 7.6 on the Richter scale, has also
injured 4,000 people and left nearly 3,000 trapped in collapsed
buildings.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister's message also expressed concern over Thai
nationals working in Taiwan, saying that the government was trying
its best to help and alleviate difficulties confronting them, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said that at least one Thai worker has been confirmed dead
and six others injured in the worst quake in Taiwan in a century.
The identities of the Thai casualties have not yet confirmed.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister has instructed the Foreign Ministry and the
Labor and Social Welfare Ministry to set up centers in key cities
in Taiwan to assist Thai workers and assess humanitarian needs
there.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, centers have been set up in Bangkok and northeastern
provinces, from where a number of Thais have gone to work in
Taiwan, to help give information to their relatives.
</P>
<P>
There are about 140,000 Thai workers in Taiwan, most of them
reportedly stay out of the quake-hit areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
