<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Callens Advances to Luxembourg Open Quarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Els Callens, who got into the
Luxembourg Open women's tournament when America Serena Williams
withdrew, won her first match on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Callens beat Barbara Schwartz of Austria 7-6 (8-6), 6-3 in her
opening match and reached the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
Williams withdrew from the tournament on Tuesday, saying she
was exhausted after three straight weeks of tennis. That gave
Callens, a Belgian, a berth as a lucky loser from the qualifying
round.
</P>
<P>
On a good day for Belgians, she was joined by No. 2 seed
Dominique Van Roost in the quarterfinals. Van Roost rallied from
one set down to upset Anne-Gaelle Sidot of France 4-6, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
A third Belgian, qualifier Kim Clijsters, also advanced after
romped Slovenia's Katarina Srebotnik 6-1, 6-1 to reach the second
round.
</P>
<P>
In other action Wednesday, sixth-seeded Silvia Farina of Italy
dispatched France's Sarah Pitkowski 6-1, 6-4 to move into the
quarterfinals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Sees Fast Recovery From Crisis in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) said the macroeconomic performance of the crisis-hit
economies in Asia has continued to improve in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Positive GDP growth is expected in almost all countries in the
region in 1999 as a whole, with projections in some cases revised
up substantially, the IMF said in its World Economic Outlook
released here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The financial crisis in Asia is largely over," said Michael
Mussa, IMF economic counselor and director of the Research
Department, at a press conference here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said South Korea, Indonesia, Malaysia, Thailand and the
Philippines should end up with a substantially better economic
performance this year and next than estimated earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
"Stronger growth is projected for 2000 in most countries as the
recent improvements in economic confidence and activity are
followed by a broader-based pickup in domestic demand," the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Exports have generally increased, supported by competitive
exchange rates and improved growth in regional trading partners,
said the report. The bottoming out of some commodity prices and an
upturn in the electronics industry have also helped to underpin
the recovery.
</P>
<P>
The partial recovery of capital inflows has eased financing
constraints in most cases, and the rise in confidence, along with
declining inflation, has permitted further monetary easing. Fiscal
policy also continues to play an important supportive role.
</P>
<P>
A resumption of inventory accumulation is being felt as well,
while weather-related turnarounds in agriculture are also
contributing to growth in Indonesia and the Philippines, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
However, the report cautioned that for the recovery to be
sustainable, there is an agenda of structural reforms still to be
completed.
</P>
<P>
"Reforms in the corporate sector are lagging behind in all the
crisis countries, and past experience from many other countries
points to the risk that losses in this sector, rather than being
borne by corporate shareholders, may be largely shifted to the
financial system and ultimately to taxpayers through repeated
recapitalizations of banks," the report said.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has been recovering at a surprising fast pace from
the sharp contraction of 1998, backed by supportive macroeconomic
policies.
</P>
<P>
In Malaysia, a strong economic recovery is also now under way
in response to fiscal and monetary stimulus and the pegging of the
exchange rate at a competitive level.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand also the recovery has strengthened, the report
said. A range of indicators point to an increase in consumer
spending, and net exports have also picked up.
</P>
<P>
The hardest-hit crisis economy in Asia, Indonesia, now also
seems to have turned around, and although real GDP is still
projected to decline a little further in 1999 as a whole, positive
growth resumed in the first half.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, a turnaround in agriculture and rising
exports are supporting a broader pickup in domestic output and
spending.
</P>
<P>
Following the weakening of activity in 1998, a strong economic
recovery is under way in Singapore, with growth of 4-5 percent
expected in 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
There are also recent signs of an economic turnaround in
China's Hong Kong Special Administrative Region. Led by a rebound
in private consumption, output rose sharply in the second quarter
this year after five consecutive quarters of decline.
</P>
<P>
China has weathered the effects of the Asian crisis relatively
well, aided by fiscal stimulus in mid-1998, and also by its
relatively strong external position, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
