<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Seeks More Sufficient Action on Debt Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Zambia said Wednesday
that the international community should take more sufficient
actions on debt relief for the poor nations, in order to pave the
way for the economic development in the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Zambian President Frederick Chiluba was
addressing the General Assembly here.
</P>
<P>
"External debt remains both a burden and a major impediment to
the development process of many developing countries, including my
country Zambia," he said.
</P>
<P>
"While we welcome the recent outcome of the G-8 Summit held in
Cologne, Germany, on the Highly Indebted Poor Countries
initiative, the measures for faster, broader and deeper debt
relief, in our view, are not sufficient to resolve the external
debt problem of developing countries, especially the poorest among
them, unless they are translated in real tangible, practical,
economic, development programs," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is the view of my government that the G-8 target of debt
relief of about 100 billion U.S. dollars for the poorest countries
in the world, the majority of whom are in Africa, will have little
effect on the problem unless the terms of the Heavily Indebted
Poor Countries initiative are further revised in such a way
as to make them more flexible and tailored to suit the specific
conditions of the targeted countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Many of us in the developing countries understand that, in
order to survive and contribute positively in the global markets,
we need to make our economies more competitive," he said.
</P>
<P>
"These challenges cannot be wished away, neither can they be
remedied by empty statements," he said. "Global poverty will only
be eradicated by a concerted global program."
</P>
<P>
"By solving the issue of poverty, the world will solve the
problem of conflict and instability in the developing countries,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president voiced his deep concerns over "the
continued deterioration of the financial situation of the United
Nations."
</P>
<P>
"This situation is well known to all of us in this Assembly, as
it has been the focus of our discussions for the past five years
now," he said. "The reform of the United Nations will not be
implemented effectively if the financial situation is not
seriously addressed."
</P>
<P>
"It is the inescapable duty of all of us to honor our
obligations by ensuring that we pay our assessed contributions in
full, on time, and without conditions," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
