<HEADLINE> Clinton Hopeful on DPRK's Pledge on Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton Wednesday expressed the hope that the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) would commit itself to a pledge not to
test a long-range missile after the United States partially lifted
sanctions last week.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, when asked by reporters at the White House whether he
believed the DPRK would hold to its commitment, said, "I do. And
of course, if the future proves otherwise, there are always other
options open to us."
</P>
<P>
During talks in Berlin, Germany, on Sept. 7-12, the United
States promised to ease the sanctions in return for the DPRK's
pledge not to engage in a missile test launch, which was said to
be accepted by Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the mutual compromise between Washington and
Pyongyang would contribute to the easing of tensions on the Korean
Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very, very hopeful about it. If it works, it does," he
said. Under the easing of sanctions, trade in most consumer goods,
commercial transport of cargo and passengers, and funds transfers
between individuals in the U.S. and DPRK will be allowed in most
cases.
</P>
<P>
Investment in raw materials sectors including agriculture,
petroleum and timber, as well as in infrastructure and tourism,
also will be permitted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
