<HEADLINE> Improved U.S.-DPRK Ties to Help Better Seoul-Pyongyang Relations: Kim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Dae-
jung said Wednesday that improved relations between the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) and the United States will help
better relations between Seoul and Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
Kim made the remarks at a meeting with visiting U.S coordinator
for DPRK policy William Perry, who arrived here earlier in the day
for a one-day visit.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Kim spoke highly of Perry for his "active
and sincere attitude" over his report of policy recommendation to
U.S. President Bill Clinton and the Congress, calling the report "
realistic."
</P>
<P>
Kim said further Washington-Tokyo-Seoul cooperation will be
very important in helping the implementation of Perry's report.
</P>
<P>
Perry, the former U.S. defense secretary, said his report based
on President Kim's "sunshine policy" to Pyongyang is a product of
Washington-Tokyo-Seoul cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In his three-stage-goal report, Perry said a short-term goal is
to create an atmosphere conducive to the DPRK's suspension of its
test-firing of long-range missiles in exchange for Washington's
lifting of economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
It is Perry's first visit to Seoul after Clinton announced last
week to ease trade and economic sanctions against Pyongyang.
</P>
</TEXT>
