<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Troops Departs For East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 22 (Xinhua) -- An Italian navy transport ship
weighed anchor Wednesday night at the Italian central port of
Livorno, bound for East Timor with Folgore and Carabinieri
paratroopers, vehicles and supplies aboard.
</P>
<P>
Six hundred Italian soldiers will participate in the U.N.
mission in the ex-Portuguese colony, with a company of 200
parachute troops expected to arrive on the island before the end
of the month, the Italian Defense Ministry said earlier.
</P>
<P>
Most troops, equipment and supplies will be transported by sea
on board the San Giusto, which recently took part in humanitarian
operations for earthquake-stricken Turkey, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Present for the departure of the transport ship from the port,
Italian Defense Undersecretary Paolo Guerrini said the
peacekeeping mission was agreed to "also on the recommendation of
the Italian government which very strongly urged" the initiative.
</P>
<P>
The paratroopers aboard the San Giusto will reach Townsville,
Australia, and then the East Timorese capital of Dili after about
four weeks at sea.
</P>
<P>
The troops will be joining an 8,000-strong force in which there
will be 4,500 Australians. About 2,000 Australians with British
Gurkhas and troops from New Zealand have already landed on the
island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
