<HEADLINE> U.N. Lauds Central African Republic for Peaceful Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Wednesday congratulated the Central African Republic
for its people's "maturity and calm" during the first round of
presidential elections in the country.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here through his spokesman, Annan
expressed "his satisfaction at the peaceful and calm manner in
which the people of the Central African Republic have participated
in the vote."
</P>
<P>
"The significant turnout underlines their desire for stability,
democracy and development," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general congratulates all political participants
and the people of the Central African Republic on their display of
maturity and calm during this democratic event," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general also would like to extend his deep
appreciation to the Special Representative of the
Secretary-General, Oluyemi Adeniji, the civilian and military
personnel of the United Nations Mission in the Central African
Republic (MINURCA) and all electoral observers for their excellent
work in supporting the elections, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Elections for a new president in the Central African Republic
were largely trouble-free Sunday despite charges of voter fraud
and fears of political bloodshed, a senior U.N. peacekeeper was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Turnout in Sunday's elections was estimated by some observers
at around 60 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
