<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0350 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Urges New Approaches for Broad-Based Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Wednesday
urged the international community to formulate new approaches for
broad-based development, guided by the need for economic equality
for individuals and nations.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 54th session of the United Nations General
Assembly, Pakistan's Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz said free
markets and free political systems are rapidly integrating the
world across frontiers and continents, and most developing
countries have been bypassed by the benefits of globalization.
</P>
<P>
"In trade, we need a truly level playing field to ensure
greater balance in the benefits of a rules-based multilateral
trading system for the developing countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In finance, we need a more stable financial order which can
control the volatility of capital flows, make available adequate
liquidity, especially for developing countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In technology, with an increasingly knowledge-based global
economy, the technology gap must be rapidly narrowed. To this end,
it would be useful to evolve global principles and guidelines for
access to and transfer of technology," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990923.0351 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Advocates Role of State, Importance of Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- India Wednesday
emphasized the role of state in a globalizing world and the
importance of development to enhancing human rights.
</P>
<P>
It would be an error to assume that the days of the state are
over, said Indian Foreign Minister Jaswant Singh at the general
debate of the 54th Session of the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The state and national sovereignties continue to have a crucial
role and relevance today, he said, noting that "there is no
substitute to the sovereign state, even gobolization can but work
through state intermediaries only."
</P>
<P>
The state needs to be strengthened, Singh said, adding that to
diminish, marginalize or to ignore the state would be "bad
practice" because "the weaker the state is rendered, the less
shall it be able to promote the interests of its citizens."
</P>
<P>
Turning to the relationship between human rights and
development, the minister said human rights requires economic
growth because many of the deprivations faced by individuals are
rooted in marginalization created by poverty.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, development should be "the cross-cutting theme of
the United Nations" and the multilateral development system must
be strengthened, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
